<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Elephant Born in Swaziland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The first elephant calf
born in Swaziland in more than one century has made its
appearance at the Mkyhaya game reserve, South African Press
Association (SAPA) quoted a Swazi source as reporting today.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland's indigenous elephant were hunted to the point of
extinction more than a hundred years ago.
</P>
<P>
The new calf is a reward of a project initiated in 1986 to
rebuild Swaziland's elephant population, Swaziland big game parks
spokesman Neliwe Shabangu was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Shabangu said that elephant were reintroduced to the Hlane
royal national park and Mkhaya game reserve between 1986 and 1994
with the assistance of national parks board of South Africa and
worldwide fund for Nature South Africa.
</P>
<P>
There are now about 40 elephant in Swaziland, most of them
from South Africa's Kruger national park, more than 500 km
northeast of Pretoria, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea to Guarantee Financial Institutions' Credit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government has
decided to guarantee the country's financial institutions'
payments of external debts, Vice Premier and Minister of Finance
and Economy Kang Kyong-shik said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an economic ministers' meeting, Kang said the
government will also extend special loans of up to 4 trillion won
(about 4.4 billion U.S. dollars) to banks to bail them out of the
financial crisis deepened by bankruptcies and near-insolvencies of
major conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
The moves are primarily designed to stabilize the domestic
financial market and to prop up the country's financial
institutions' overseas credit standing, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government has planned to raise the stock
investment ceiling for foreigners to 26 percent of a listed
domestic firm next month from the existing 23 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Expanding foreign stock investment along with a set of similar
measures will bring an additional foreign exchange liquidity of
eight to 8.5 billion dollars into the domestic financial sector,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Government measures also include a wide opening of the domestic
bond market, an increase of overseas borrowing through
government-run banks, an extension of usance period and a removal
of limits on receipts of advance payments for exports.
</P>
<P>
The government will allow the financially-troubled banks,
including the Korea First Bank, to make rights issues and
undertake them through issuing bonds after acquiring the National
Assembly's approval, he said.
</P>
<P>
Korea First is the main creditor bank of the bankrupt Hanbo and
Sammi steel groups as well as the largest lender to the
near-insolvent Kia Group.
</P>
<P>
"Those financial institutions to receive the preferential
loans, however, will be obliged to make stringent self-rescue
efforts so as to normalize their management in three to five years
from now," the deputy premier said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
