<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation in Western Germany to Top 2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The inflation rate in the western
half of Germany is expected to jump to a 28-month high of 2
percent in August, up from 1.7 percent in July, the German federal
statistics office said today.
</P>
<P>
The Wiesbaden-based office, which based its projection on
preliminary data from four western German states, said rising fuel
prices due to the stronger U.S. dollar were to be blamed for the
latest increase in German inflation.
</P>
<P>
The larger-than-expected inflation rate is likely to reinforce
market speculations that the German central bank, the Bundesbank,
would be forced to raise interest rates which could curb price
hikes.
</P>
<P>
But many observers in the German financial capital of Frankfurt
did not expect the Bundesbank to take such a move at its Tuesday
meeting when it is due to conduct its weekly review of a key
benchmark rate, the securities repurchase rate.
</P>
<P>
Given the recent weakness of the dollar, the central bankers
would take some time to examine the price-related factors exactly,
an economist with the German Commerzbank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Progressing Forward in Financial Reform (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- China has made remarkable
progress in financial reform, and the development of its capital
market, a Chinese banker said at the ninth annual PACAP Finance
Conference held here today.
</P>
<P>
Yin Jieyan, vice-governor of the People's bank of China, the
central bank, said that China has made a breakthrough to reform
its foreign exchange system, and current accounts of Chinese
Renminbi have become convertible freely with foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
Commercial banking businesses have been separated from policy
businesses, and the reform of the country's financial system is
progressing smoothly, he said.
</P>
<P>
China has set up a sound financial system at a preliminary
stage, guided by the central bank, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Multiple financial institutes co-exist under such a system, but
state-owned commercial banks are still playing a leading role, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Yin said that China will approve 14 new commercial banks to be
set up, of which 10 are share-holding banks.
</P>
<P>
The number of cooperative banks in both rural and urban areas
has been increasing rapidly over the past few years,
</P>
<P>
The banker said that a healthy development has also
been seen in the non-banking sector over the past years.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, this year, the country has had numerous
non-banking institutes in various forms, including 94 securities
companies, 245 trust and investment companies, and 14 insurers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China is speeding up opening-up of its financial
sector, Yin said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, about 540 overseas banks and other
financial institutes have opened representative offices in China,
and nine overseas banks have been licensed to do Renminbi-based
business in the Pudong New Area of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
He said that China will continues the pilot operation for
overseas banks to do Renminbi-based business, which means that
overseas banks will have more development opportunities in China.
</P>
<P>
China's capital market has been developing quickly over the
past years, and the size of China's stock market has been
expanding quickly, he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
