<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Not to Revise Strategy Toward Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Greek Cypriot Side will
not revise its strategy toward a Cyprus solution in spite of
recent deadlock in the U.N.-led direct talks between the Greek
and Turkish Cypriot sides, a senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the 10th World Conference
of Overseas Cypriots here on behalf of President Glafcos
Clerides, Foreign Minister Ioaanis Kasoulides said recent direct
talks in Glion, Switzerland, failed to overcome the impasse.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that "this is not the end of the world and
does not imply we should revise our planned strategy or course."
</P>
<P>
The four-day conference, with the participation of
represenatives of overseas Cypriots from more than eight
countries, will discuss ways to promote a settlement of the
Cyprus problem and solve problems the overseas Cypriots face in
their host countries.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides told the delegates that it is the beginning of a
course by which the international community, based on
U.N. resolutions on Cyprus, will proceed to overturn the
unacceptable status quo on the island.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government, he assured, will show constructive
political will for a solution and at the same time its
commitment to internationally accepted principles and human
rights.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides urged the international community to persuade
Turkey through friendly means and if necessary by imposing
sanctions to abandon its intransigent stance and assist toward a
Cyprus settlement.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister made special mention of the close and
harmonious cooperation between the governments of Cyprus and
Greece, noting that their efforts and those of overseas Cypriots
and Greeks have contributed to attracting greater international
interest to the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Also addressing the conference, President of the International
Federation of Overseas Cypriots, George Christofides, called on
Cyprus, Greece and Hellenes of the diaspora to coordinate their
actions and speak with one voice.
</P>
<P>
He said that after the failure of two rounds of direct
negotiations between President Clerides and Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash in the U.S. and Switzerland, it is necessary
that the Greek Cypriot side re-consolidates its strength and
tactics in the direction of realising its rightful claims and
taking advantage of every measure of strength that Hellenism now
possesses in all parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into a Greek Cypriot controlled south
and a Turkish-occupied north since Turkey invaded and occupied
the northern third of the island in 1974 in the wake of a
short-lived coup by supporters of union with Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
