<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, August 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN -- Egon Krenz, the last leader of the former East Germany,
was sentenced Monday by a Berlin court to six and a half years in
prison in connection with killings along the Berlin Wall during
the Cold War era.
</P>
<P>
Krenz, 60, was convicted of manslaughter related to the death
of people shot by East German border guards when trying to flee
East Germany through the former border areas along the Berlin
Wall. (Germany-Krenz-Conviction)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl flatly rejected repeated
calls for a cabinet reshuffle by Finance Minister Theo Waigel on
his first day back to work from a four-week vacation.
</P>
<P>
"I do not plan to reshuffle the cabinet. There is absolutely no
reason to do so," Kohl told the mass circulation newspaper Bild in
an interview to be published on Tuesday, copies of which were made
available in advance to reporters. (Germany-Cabinet)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Tobacco has become a greater cause of death and
disability than any single disease, the World Health Organization
warned here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Tobacco use has reached the proportion of a global epidemic,"
since it causes three million deaths annually around the world,
WHO announced in a press conference of the ongoing 10th World
Conference on Tobacco or Health.
</P>
<P>
The mortality will rise to ten million each year 20 years
later, including seven millions in developing
countries. (Tobacco-Mortality)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- Visiting Chinese Premier Li Peng and Singapore
Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong reviewed here Monday the development
of the Sino-Singapore relations in recent years and expressed
their satisfaction with the fruitful cooperation between the two
countries in all fields.
</P>
<P>
During their discussion, held in the Presidential Palace
Istana, Li Peng noted that in the seven years since the
establishment of diplomatic relations between the two countries,
bilateral ties have developed rapidly, featuring frequent exchange
of visits by top-level leaders and increased bilateral trade and
investment.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu met his
Japanese counterpart Ryutaro Hashimoto Monday, seeking for more
investment and help on water development projects.
</P>
<P>
During his two-hour meeting with Hashimoto, Netanyahu conveyed
a joint appeal from Israel and Jordan's King Hussein for Japanese
support for a water purification project. (Japan-Israel) 
</P>
</TEXT>
