<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investment in UAE Reaches 11 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Investment in the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) exceeded 11 billion U.S. dollars in 1996, most of
which came from the private sector, the UAE's Wam news agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Public and private investment in the UAE stood at around 11.1
billion dollars last year, compared with some 10.8 billion dollars
in 1995, Wam said.
</P>
<P>
The investment from the private sector accounted for nearly 66
percent of the total amount, standing at nearly 7.41 billion
dollars in 1996, it said.
</P>
<P>
It gave no figures for investment in the oil sector, which is
considered to be the major part of the country's economy, but
industry sources said nearly 1.9 billion dollars had been pumped
into this sector annually over the past six years.
</P>
<P>
Like other Gulf Arab states, the UAE has embarked on projects
to boost oil output capacity to face growing domestic and foreign
demand.
</P>
<P>
Currently, its oil output stands at around 2.5 million barrels
per day (bpd) and it is planning to increase the annual production
to some 3 million bpd in the next few years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some Bosses Deserve High Pay, Says Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Managers in British privatized
utilities are underpaid by an average of 6 percent than their
counterparts in companies of similar size, according to a new
study released here today.
</P>
<P>
The study by Crisp Consulting which advises regulated
industries, and the Center for Economics and Business Research,
comes amid general concern in Britain that the pay of utilities'
directors rose disproportionately quickly after the companies were
privatized.
</P>
<P>
The study of pay levels at 75 FTSE 100 companies, concluded
that most privatized utility bosses were paid less than their
experience and company performance and size demanded.
</P>
<P>
It took into account directors' experience, the company's
market capitalization and their performance in generating
shareholder value.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, Severn Trent's Victor Cocker, Ian
Robinson of Scottish-Power and Southern Electricity's Henry Casley
are among the most underpaid directors.
</P>
<P>
By contrast, Roger Leverton, who has since been removed from
his post as group chief executive at Pilkingtonk, received almost
twice as much as would be expected elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
"This study destroys a generally accepted myth about boardroom
pay," said John Hatch, executive chairman of Crisp Consulting.
</P>
<P>
Deborah Barlow, an author of the study, said that some of the
bosses in the privatized companies received 42 percent less than
directors in similar companies and with similar experience and
performance.
</P>
<P>
The study also claimed that a number of directors elsewhere in
the private sector were overpaid, some earning almost twice their
fair value, according to the model used in the study. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt Rejects Talks with Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's ruling Kenya African
National Union (KANU) failed to attend constitutional talks with
the National Coalition Executive Committee (NCEC) this morning
and the latter is threatening another national strike.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Vice President George Saitoti, who led the 37-member
KANU negotiation team, told reporters later that KANU will only
consult with legal opposition groups in parliament, instead of
the unregistered NCEC.
</P>
<P>
The NCEC, which is comprised of opposition parties to
coordinate campaign for constitutional reforms, was set up in
April by National Convention Assembly.
</P>
<P>
According to Saitoti, NCEC is a non-elected body without a
mandate, and therefore will not be recognized by KANU.
</P>
<P>
NCEC held the first round of reform talks anyway without KANU
attendance. After the meeting, the 65-member NCEC team announced
in a statement that it will call national strike again and the
detailed strike plan will be finished later this week.
</P>
<P>
NCEC will resume mass actions until the government shifts its
stand and holds talks with it, said the NCEC statement.
</P>
<P>
Saitoti stressed that the NCEC "objectives and methods are
sure recipe for chaos and civil war."
</P>
<P>
"KANU has consistently insisted that the envisaged dialogue
and consultation is with the opposition in parliament," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he reiterated KANU's "commitment to dialogue and
consultations with the opposition to ensure that necessary
reforms are undertaken in an orderly, peaceful and legal manner."
</P>
<P>
Violence has been escalating in the east African country since
May when the opposition started attempts to launch rallies and
strikes in a bid to press for constitutional reforms before the
general election, whose date is yet to be fixed.
</P>
<P>
Under the current constitution, any candidate, if he wins no
less than 25 percent of votes respectively in five of the eight
provinces of Kenya, he can be qualified as a legal president.
</P>
<P>
Now the opposition urges to change the clause, demanding the
future president get more than 50 percent of the total votes
nationwide, otherwise form a coalition government with other
parties. This has already been refused by Kenyan President Daniel
arap Moi, who has been in power since 1978. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
