<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Accounts Holders Dissatisfied With Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Almost 16 million holders of
current accounts are missing out on more than 130 million pounds
(208 million US dollars) a year in interest, according to the
latest banking survey from Abbey National.
</P>
<P>
A quarter of all current accounts pay no interest. Among those
surveyed who were receiving interest, a third were dissatisfied
with the rate.
</P>
<P>
The worst deal is from Lloyds, which pays only 1.20 pounds
(1.92 US dollars) a year on an account with an average monthly
balance of 750 pounds (1,200 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Mildland and NatWest both pay 1.50 pounds (2.4 US dollars) and
Barclays 1.80 pounds (2.88 US dollars). The best accounts pay 8.37
pounds (13.39 US dollars) (Abbey National) and 4.19 pounds (6.70
US dollars) (TSB).
</P>
<P>
Most banks and building societies pay a flat rate of interest
irrespective of the account balance.
</P>
<P>
So customers keeping large account balances with NatWest and
Midland earn just 0.25 percent a year, while Barclays' customers
earn 0.3 percent and Lloyds' receive 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Recently converted building societies Abbey National and
Woolwich pay 3.5 percent on balances of more than 25,000 pounds
(40,000 US dollars), beating the mutual Nationwide, which offers
3.25 percent, and Alliance &AMP; Leicester with 3 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
