<HEADLINE> Zambia Calls for Great Regional Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Zambia today urged African
countries to make more rapid advance toward greater economic
integration at sub-regional and regional levels.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Lawrence Shimba said here that the
governments in the region have realized the need to come together
to coordinate their policies so as to benefit from the advantages
derived from economies of scale through regional integration.
</P>
<P>
He was opening a workshop jointly organized by the Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) and the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) on regional policy program
and project management.
</P>
<P>
Shimba said that without a strong political commitment toward
integration, it will be difficult to translate treaties and other
instruments into practical and implementable measures.
</P>
<P>
many african countries have realized that it is only with the
private sector taking the lead in the production, distribution
and marketing of goods and services that meaningful progress will
be possible, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Speaking earlier, acting COMESA Secretary General Erastus
Mwencha expressed his hope that the workshop aims to enhance
technical knowledge and that skills would come first.
</P>
<P>
He said there is a general consensus among the COMESA member
states on the need for Africa to be more economically and
politically integrated.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha said the proposed COMESA timetable for the attainment
of a free trade area, a common external tariff, a customs union
and a single currency is realistic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
