<HEADLINE> Mozambique's Cashew Industry Faces Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Another cashew processing
factory has shut down in Mozambique due to lack of raw materials,
the Southern African Broadcasting Association reported today.
</P>
<P>
The plant at Manjacaze in the southern province of Gaza closed
last Wednesday due to lack of raw materials, and all 398 workers
at the factory have been laid off.
</P>
<P>
This brings to four the number of cashew processing plants
which have shut down in Mozambique because of the shortage of
nuts to shell.
</P>
<P>
Only 10 cashew processing plants remain operational in the
southern African country, with some of them expected to close
later this year, the report quoted a local daily The Noticias as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The closures are blamed on the government's policy to allow
the export of raw, unprocessed nuts to India and some other
countries.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique's cashew industrial experts and trade union leaders
have been united in opposing the government's trade policy which
is being implemented at the instigation of the World Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
