<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Experts to Repair Liberia's Telecom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 25 (Xinhua) -- West African countries will send
a team of experts to assess the state of the telecommunications
network of Liberia devastated in the seven-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
A draft rehabilitation plan is to be produced following the
on-the-spot inspection by the experts sent by the executive
secretariat of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS), the News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
A similar team will also visit the country to explore the
possibility of computerizing its customs administration, the
report said, quoting acting Executive Secretary Ouhoumoudou
Mahamadhou.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the dispatch of the two teams reflects the
desire of the 16-member organization to contribute to its
economic reintegration to the existing sub-regional schemes, some
of which eluded the country during the bloody civil war.
</P>
<P>
With the new government already in place, Liberia should focus
on new challenges that need to be speedily addressed, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Foremost among these are the issues of repatriation and
reintegration of refugees, rehabilitation of basic
infrastructure, national reconstruction and reintegration of
former solders," the acting executive secretary added.
</P>
<P>
The official made the remarks at an ECOWAS council of
ministers meeting which is scheduled to end today in Abuja,
capital of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
On the situation in Sierra Leone, he said, the crisis, which
came on the heels of the conclusion of the Liberian peace plan,
demonstrated the need for ECOWAS to consider the possibility of
introducing the community instruments envisaged in this area as
part of efforts to promote sub-regional stability.
</P>
<P>
Some soldiers launched a military coup on May 25 and overthrew
the legitimate government there. The international community
strongly condemns the coup and ECOWAS has tightened embargo and
sanctions against the country in a bid to force the coupists to
hand over power to the ousted government.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting is expected to review the performance of
sub-regional economic integration programs and propose solutions
to overcome identified bottlenecks to the ECOWAS summit.
</P>
<P>
Sub-regional peace and stability is projected to be high on
the agenda of the two-day summit, scheduled for the coming
Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
