<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Florida's Lawsuit Against Tobacco Industry Settled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Florida state and the
tobacco industry ended their dispute today with the signing of an
11.3 billion dollars settlement of a lawsuit intended to punish
cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Florida Governor Lawton Chiles and
tobacco industry lawyer Arthur Golden in court today before Palm
Beach County Circuit Judge Harold Cohen.
</P>
<P>
In the lawsuit, the state asked for 12.3 billion dollars --
1.3 billion dollars for tax money spent treating sick smokers
without insurance and 11 billion dollars to punish the industry.
</P>
<P>
The state won on three important battlegrounds: "protecting
Florida's children, making tobacco pay for the damage it has cost
our taxpayers and for cigarette makers to finally tell the truth,"
said April Herrle, a spokeswoman for Chiles.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the financial settlement, the industry agrees to
pull down all of its billboards within six months and start with
signs within 1,000 feet of schools. Vending machines where
children have access would be removed, and outdoor advertising in
sporting arenas and on mass transit would be banned.
</P>
<P>
The trial began in jury selection on August 1. In depositions,
tobacco executives had already conceded that smoking is harmful
and can cause deadly diseases.
</P>
<P>
The American Lung Association in Washington called the
agreement "significant."
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Geoffrey Bible, the head of Philip Morris Cos.,
conceded in a deposition that smoking might have caused as many as
100,000 deaths. On Friday, Steven Goldstone, head of RJR Nabisco,
also said in a deposition that he believed "smoking plays a part
in causing lung cancer."
</P>
<P>
Florida is the second state to reach an agreement to recover
the Medicaid funds. On July 3, Mississippi state settled its
lawsuit against the tobacco industry, which agreed to pay nearly
3.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In Philadelphia today, U.S. District Judge Clarence Newcomer
certified a pending smokers' lawsuit as a class action and set a
trial date of October 14. The lawsuit represents some 10 million
smokers who say they were addicted and are seeking medical
monitoring for smoking-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. Congress is looking over a proposed 368.5
billion dollar national settlement with 40 states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
