<HEADLINE> ILO Business Workshop Opened in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 25 (Xinhua) -- A regional workshop of the
International Labor Organization (ILO) opened here today to draw
up strategies for an integrated "Start Your Business" (SYB)
program.
</P>
<P>
Opening the two-day workshop, Alois Mangwende, Zimbabwe's
Deputy Minister of Public Service, Labor and Social Welfare,
pointed out the importance of the meeting, saying it attempted to
resolve the issues of poverty alleviation, unemployment, the
right to work and sustainable economic development.
</P>
<P>
The SYB program, he said, was also a source of ownership and
management opportunities for women who often were held back by
lack of access to productive assets.
</P>
<P>
The SYB program started in July 1994 as a pilot project in
Uganda and Zimbabwe, and initially trained 200 people in business
skills.
</P>
<P>
The successes from the pilot program culminated in the
inclusion of Zambia and the fully-fledged launch of the program
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
There were 15 participating organizations in the three
countries and to date more than 600 persons have benefited from
the program, Mangwende added.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is being attended by 44 participants from Uganda,
Zambia, Sweden, Switzerland, South Africa, Ethiopia, Namibia,
Lesotho and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
