<HEADLINE> Arafat: No Change in Albright's Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat today denied reports that
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has changed her mind on
her upcoming visit to the region.
</P>
<P>
"There has been no change in the program of Albright's visit to
the region," Arafat told reporters following talks with President
Hosni Mubarak in the Egyptian port city of Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
Today's summit was held in anticipation of the long-overdue
visit by the U.S. leader to the region, scheduled for sometime in
September, in a bid to revive the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also denied reports that the visit of U.S. Peace
Coordinator Dennis Ross to the region early this month aimed at
delaying Albright's visit.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian security officials have been meeting with their
Israeli and U.S. counterparts under a framework set up earlier
this month during Ross' visit.
</P>
<P>
Albright has said her prospective trip to the region depends on
progress on security. Her mission will be to salvage peace talks
battered by the Israeli new settlement building and the July 30
Jerusalem suicide bombings.
</P>
<P>
The PNA leader said the Palestinian side has shown cooperation
in the field of security in accordance with the signed agreements
and within the Palestinian law.
</P>
<P>
Arafat strongly denounced the "Israeli plots to sabotage the
Palestinian leaderships and opposition factions."
</P>
<P>
"It was officially reported in Israeli newspapers that a
(Israeli) unit was formed to work in Palestinian territories to
liquidate Palestinian leaderships," he said, adding that nobody
can intimidate the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
Arafat thanked Egypt for the multi-million-dollar aid to the
Palestinians who are suffering from the Israeli economic sanctions
and said Algeria and Morocco have offered similar donations.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak issued a decree last week to transfer 10 million
U.S. dollars in aid to the PNA to relieve the Palestinian
sufferings. The Israeli punitive clampdown following the July 30
Jerusalem suicide bombings which killed 16 people has deprived
tens of thousands of Palestinians of work or salary.
</P>
<P>
He said Mubarak has briefed him on an urgent donation from
Sheikh Zayed Ben Sultan, head of the United Arab Emirates and
another aid from Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Arafat renewed his call for convening an Arab summit to come up
with unified Arab strategy to face up to the major issues of the
Mideast peace process, including Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"This summit should discuss the future of Jerusalem, to
preserve it as the capital of the Palestinian state and as a holy
place for both Muslims and Christians," he added.
</P>
<P>
The construction of a new settlement in East Jerusalem in March
put the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks on hold. And the double
bombings last month upset a promised resumption of the
negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
