<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- A former Ku Klux Klansman was
sentenced to 15 years in federal prison today for conspiring to
burn a rural black church and a migrant labor camp, the Associated
Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Hubert Rowell will also be on probation for five years after
his release from prison. He and Arthur A. Haley, another former
Klan member, pleaded guilty last December to four counts. Both of
them admitted conspiring in the 1995 burnings of Macedonia Baptist
Church and a migrant labor camp in Clarendon County.
</P>
<P>
Haley was sentenced earlier this month to 21 and a half years
in prison.
</P>
<P>
While neither Rowell nor Haley were charged with setting the
church fire, prosecutors said Haley provided flammable liquids and
Rowell mixed them and told two other men, Gary Christopher Cox and
Timothy Adron Welch, how to apply them.
</P>
<P>
Norton already has sentenced Cox to 19 and a half years and
Welch to 18 years in prison. Both men also had Klan ties. 
</P>
