<HEADLINE> Former East German Leader to Appeal Against Court Rule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Egon Krenz, the last leader of
the former East Germany, said today that he would appeal against a
rule by a Berlin court which sentenced him to six and a half years
in prison in connection with killings along the Berlin Wall during
the Cold War era.
</P>
<P>
In a prepared statement read by his son Carsten to a news
conference after the trial, Krenz said he was the victim of a
political trial and was sentenced without committing any crime.
</P>
<P>
He called on members of the United Nations (UN) to intervene as
a former UN member (East Germany) was being criminalized by the
German court.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that he would not ask for a pardon from Bonn.
</P>
<P>
His lawyer, Robert Unger, said he would appeal to the German
supreme court within one week and, if necessary, to the German
constitutional court and the European Court of Human Rights in
Strasbourg, France.
</P>
<P>
Krenz, 60, was convicted today of manslaughter related to the
death of people shot by East German border guards when trying to
flee East Germany through the former border areas along the Berlin
Wall.
</P>
<P>
He was placed under arrest and brought to the Moabit remand
prison in Berlin immediately after the trial.
</P>
<P>
The Berlin court today also sentenced two other members of the
former East German Politburo, Guenter Schabowski, 68, and Guenther
Kleiber, 65, to three years in jail on similar charges.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German RTL television today, former
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev also criticized the trial, saying
that it violated the German reunification accord, which had spoken
of the former East Germany and West Germany as two sovereign
states.
</P>
<P>
As the last state and party leader of East Germany, Krenz had
acted within the framework of a sovereign state which had its own
laws, Gorbachev said. "There are neither legal nor moral reasons
for the convictions of Krenz and his comrades.... The trial is
nothing but politics loaded with demons of the past," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
