<HEADLINE> Egypt to Ship Food to Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will deliver a shipment of
150 tonnes of flour, 100 tonnes of sugar and 100 tonnes of rice to
the Palestinians in another move to relieve their plight under the
Israeli sanctions, the Middle East News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian assistance is to reach the Palestinian self-rule
areas via Rafah checkpoint once arrangements with the Israeli side
are finalized, said Mahmoud Karim, Egypt's Ambassador to the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
"This will greatly help the Palestinians to ride out the severe
economic situation brought about by the Israeli siege," Karim said.
</P>
<P>
Also, Egypt will allow Palestinians, who could not make it back
to their homes from holidays as a result of the Israeli embargo,
to enter Egypt. The legislative Palestinian Council had asked the
Egyptian Embassy in Gaza for that facility, he added.
</P>
<P>
Israel froze custom duties and tax revenues due to the PNA and
imposed overall closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip following
the July 30 Jerusalem suicide bombings, depriving tens of
thousands of Palestinians of their jobs and salaries.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak issued a decree last week to transfer 10 million U.S.
dollars in aid to the PNA to relieve the Palestinian sufferings.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to Egypt today, PNA President Yasser Arafat
thanked Cairo for the multi-million-dollar aid to the Palestinians
under the economic sanctions. He said Algeria and Morocco have
offered similar donations.
</P>
<P>
The construction of a new settlement in East Jerusalem in March
put the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks on hold. Double suicide
bombings in a Jerusalem market place last month upset the
resumption of the negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
