<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Become Tougher With Youth Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Justice Minister Anne
McLellan will set out harsher penalties for youths convicted for
serious and violent crimes, said a report today.
</P>
<P>
Canada is in danger of destroying and undermining the
credibility of its entire youth-offenders structure, the minister
warned in a speech to the Canadian Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
She hinted at legislating tougher sentences, prosecuting more
youths in adult court and naming some of those convicted of
violent offenses.
</P>
<P>
"For me, it's a pretty shocking statistic that six or seven out
of every 10 Canadians have no confidence in the Youth Offenders
Act," she was quoted by the Globe and Mail newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Why is that so? It's because of that very small number of
serious and violent young offenders who Canadians feel are not
being dealt with appropriately by our justice system."
</P>
<P>
"I think we need to do some rebalancing in relation to that
group of young offenders," she said.
</P>
<P>
McLellan said she was impressed with a task-force
recommendation that youths older than 14 found guilty of murder or
other violent offenses be transferred to adult court for
sentencing.
</P>
<P>
As for the 85 percent of young offenders who are guilty of less
serious crimes, she favors "restorative justice," in which
offenders make amends for their actions instead of imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Canada implemented a series of youth-justice reforms in 1995,
which saw maximum sentence for a youth found guilty of
first-degree murder increase to 10 years and the 16- and 17-year
olds charged with violent offenses face trial in adult court.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the changes were criticized as inadequate by opponents who
were seeking tougher penalties for young offenders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
