<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A new Galaxy super, mid-sized executive jet is to
be shown to investors and the media at a special roll-out
ceremony on September 4 at Ben-Gurion International Airport,
reported bi-weekly Israel Business Today.
</P>
<P>
The new aircraft, which is manufactured by an
Israeli-U.S. partnership called Galaxy Aerospace, is the result of
combined technological and financial development and management
provided by Israel Aircraft Industries and the Hyatt Corporation.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the organization said that the new Galaxy will
be the first aircraft of its kind to be capable of flying non-stop
between New York and Paris at lower operating costs than any other
business jet available on today's market. The Galaxy is designed
to accommodate between 8-19 passengers.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Microsoft has announced its intention to increase
the level of research and development activities at the Matam
high-tech industrial park south of Haifa, Israel's largest
industrial city, reported the latest issue of bi-weekly Israel
Business Today.
</P>
<P>
The global high-tech market leader has signed an agreement
with the municipal Economic Company of Haifa, which manages
the Matam park, under the terms of which Microsoft will rent
an additional 4,000 square meters of floor space within six
years. Microsoft's Matam facility currently uses 2,000 square
meters.
</P>
<P>
The agreement stipulates that Microsoft will rent all of a
new building which is currently under construction at the
Matam park, and which is due for completion in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli Ministry of Trade and Industry has
commenced negotiations with several U.S. financial organizations,
including Lehman Brothers and Salomon Brothers, with regard to
promoting joint Israel-U.S. investment in Israel's biotechnology
projects.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry's chief scientist Orna Beri is currently in the
U.S. to discuss the possibility of involving leading
U.S. investment houses in the program.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Ministry has said that it was looking to
forge cooperation agreements with investment houses and venture
capital funds which specialize in Israeli start-up companies in
the field of biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan today signed an agreement with the United
States to delay Jordan's debt repayment of 58.5 million
U.S. dollars to the U.S. until October, 2001, Radio Jordan
reported.
</P>
<P>
The reschedule was in accordance with the agreement reached on
May 23 by the creditors of the Paris Club who promised to help
Jordan postpone the payments of some 400 million dollars of
foreign debts coming due between June 1, 1997 and February 28,
1999.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian economy is much dependent on foreign aid and the
Kingdom's debt has reached 6.4 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
