<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Welcomes WTO Report on EU Beef Import Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Canada today welcomed a
favorable World Trade Organization's (WTO) panel report on the
European Union's (EU) ban on imports of its beef.
</P>
<P>
The report supports Canada's long-standing position that the
import ban imposed by the EU was "not consistent" with its
obligations under the WTO, said Sergio Marchi, Canada's
international trade minister.
</P>
<P>
"This important finding also underlines that Canada's trade
interests are best defended through a rules-based system," the
minister noted.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, the EU imposed a ban on imports of Canadian beef
produced with growth-promoting hormones. The EU said that the ban
was a health protection measure.
</P>
<P>
Canada argued that internationally accepted studies have
consistently found that the use of the growth hormones presents no
danger to beef consumers.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Canada requested a WTO dispute-settlement panel after
direct consultations with the EU failed to resolve the dispute.
</P>
<P>
The EU still has the right to appeal the finding of the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0044 </DOCNO>
