<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cote d'Ivoire Denies Mediation in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Cote d'Ivoire government
today denies allegations that it would participate in mediation
on Angolan clashes.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made here in an communique by the Cote
d'Ivoire foreign ministry to its Angolan counterpart.
</P>
<P>
This is the first reaction by the Ivorian government after the
recent visit by Jonas Savimbi, chairman of the National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) to the west African
country.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique available here, this position
taken by the Ivorian government is mainly aimed at avoiding
misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
It reiterated that with the aid of the three observer
countries, namely the United States, Russia and Portugal, the
United Nations had achieved positive results in mediating armed
clashes in Angola and that the government of Cote d'Ivoire has
never intended to participate in the mediation.
</P>
<P>
The recent meeting between Ivorian President Henry Konan Bedie
and Savimbi in Abidjan, said the communique, was proposed by the
U.S. government, in an attempt to persuade Savimbi into
cooperating with the Angolan government in the light of the
Lusaka Peace Accord signed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, it added, what Savimbi told the press on the likely
mediation by Cote d'Ivoire has nothing to do with the Ivorian
Government.
</P>
<P>
The Ivorian government believes that any parallel mediation on
the Angolan conflict would only lead to chaos and postpone the
peace process, said the communique. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
