<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EX-Irish PM Haughey Likely to Face Prosecution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Former Irish Prime Minister
Charles Haughey was likely to face criminal prosecution on charges
of accepting a large amount of cash payments from an Irish
business tycoon, press reports from Dublin said.
</P>
<P>
An official Irish government report on illegal payments to
government officials was quoted as saying today that Haughey's
initial failure to admit receiving cash payments might have
amounted to an offence and the report also called for the Director
of Public Prosecutions to make a ruling.
</P>
<P>
Haughey, three times Prime Minister, had been one of the most
powerful political leaders of Ireland. At the beginning of the
government investigation, Haughey flatly denied any allegations of
receiving any illegal cash payments but last month Haughey
admitted that he had received some 1.3 million Irish pounds (about
1.9 million U.S. dollars) from Irish businessman Ben Dunne.
</P>
<P>
Judge Brian McCracken, head of the investigation team, said
although there was no evidence that any favors had been either
sought or granted over the payments, Haughey would be charged with
hiding these payments from the tax authorities.
</P>
<P>
"It is quite unacceptable that a member of Dail Eireann
(parliament), and in particular a cabinet minister and a Taoiseach
(prime minister), should be supported in his personal lifestyle by
gifts made to him personally," McCracken said in his report.
</P>
<P>
"The attitude of Mr Charles Haughey in relation to the Tribunal
might amount to an offence. All relevant papers will be sent to
the Director of Public Prosecutions for his consideration," report
said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the report called for tougher measures on
monitoring and investigating similar cases.
</P>
<P>
Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern, a former colleague of
Haughey, has promised to take tougher measures to ensure there
should be no secret large gifts or payments to government
officials.
</P>
<P>
"I am determined to protect the integrity of our political
decision-making and to see that any attain to that integrity is
exposed," Ahern said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
