<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Jail Sued for Abusing Inmates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Missouri state officials, who
sent prisoners to live in a Brazoria County jail in Texas, today
sued the county for allegedly covering up the abuse of prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The prisoners were videotaped being bitten by a dog and shocked
by a stun gun in last September, the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
The state accused the county of breach of contract, saying that
officials there deliberately withheld information about what
happened to the Missouri prisoners in rented cells in the Brazoria
jail.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Jay Nixon, who filed the lawsuit in Cole
County Circuit Court in Missouri's capital, was quoted as saying
that the county officials had refused to turn over information,
including inmate requests for medical attention, officer reports
and medical records even though they are required to do so under
the contract with the state of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
The videotape taken at the Brazoria County Detention Center
near Houston last September by deputies for training purposes. The
videotape, surfaced earlier this month, showed deputies forcing
the newly arrived Missouri inmates to crawl on their stomachs,
zapping them with stun guns and letting an attack dog bite them.
</P>
<P>
It prompted Missouri Corrections chief Dora Schriro to pull
hundreds of inmates from Brazoria and two other Texas jails and
cancel 12 million dollars worth of contracts.
</P>
<P>
Brazoria County, Sheriff Joe King and County Judge John Willy
are named as co-defendants in the lawsuit, which seeks unspecified
monetary damages.
</P>
<P>
Prisoners were sent to three Texas jails managed by a private
company, Capital Correctional Resources Inc., because of
overcrowding in Missouri. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
