<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Science Spacecraft Launched After Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- A science spacecraft, the
Advanced Composition Explorer (ACE), was launched today from the
Cape Canaveral Air Station after a one-day delay.
</P>
<P>
A Boeing Delta II rocket carrying the ACE roared away from the
Air Station at 10:39 a.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday the launch countdown was halted by two shrimp boats
anchored in the Atlantic where the rocket's nine strap-on rocket
boosters would fall.
</P>
<P>
One was chased away, but the other did not respond to radioed
demands that it clear the area. The delay probably cost NASA
hundreds of thousands of dollars, space experts said.
</P>
<P>
Before today's launch, the U.S. Coast Guard chased one fishing
trawler out of the danger area east of Cape Canaveral, but there
was no delay.
</P>
<P>
The spacecraft was to separate from the rocket about 70 minutes
after launch and begin a long coast to a position nearly 1.6
million km from Earth.
</P>
<P>
It will provide a 30 to 60 minute warning before a potentially
dangerous solar storm strikes the Earth.
</P>
<P>
Eruptions on the surface of the sun can disrupt the Earth's
magnetic field, knocking out electrical power and endangering
spacewalking astronauts in orbit.
</P>
<P>
The ACE spacecraft's primary purpose is to sample the high
energy matter from the sun, the space between stars and from the
Milky Way that comes close to the Earth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
