<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Aviation Industry Performs Poorly in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's aviation industry has
suffered from serious setback in the past year, with big drops in
both domestic passenger movement and aircraft movement in its
three major airports.
</P>
<P>
In Lagos, the commercial hub of the country in the southwest,
the number of passengers travelling by air declined from 157,369
in January 1996 to 95,188 one year later. The figure further went
down to 87,025 in June this year.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Kano, northern Nigeria, is not anything
better with the figure dropping from 22,399 in January 1996, to
18,278 and 16,711 in January and April this year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
In Port Harcourt, the country's oil producing base in the
south, 33,658 passengers patronized airline companies in January
1996, while only 28,587 and 20,037 did so in January and May this
year respectively.
</P>
<P>
A Nigerian television authority report said today that many
passengers refused to take planes because of the poor safety
standard of the domestic airline companies.
</P>
<P>
"The companies are not taking care of what they have, so
people don't want to lose their life," a passenger was quoted as
saying in the Lagos Airport in a live broadcast.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the federal airport authority of
Nigeria admitted that poor safety was crucial to the drastic drop
in the number of passengers travelling by air, particularly
following the fatal crash of an aviation development company
passenger aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Last November, a Boeing 727 of the domestic airlines crashed
into the lagoon near Lagos, killing all the 143 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
In the same month, the number of passengers dove to 122,307
from the previous month's 178,192.
</P>
<P>
Unsatisfactory service is another major cause.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the poor performance of the aviation industry is
also witnessed in the declining aircraft movement.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, inadequate maintenance and lack of
fund as well as equipment have led to the grounding of 77
unserviceable passenger airplanes.
</P>
<P>
To date, only seven of all registered passenger planes in the
country are operating scheduled flights, it added.
</P>
<P>
As a result, aircraft movement in the airports in Lagos and
Kano went down from 4,093 and 1,058 in January 1996 to 2,575 and
440 the same month this year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The report suggested that measures should be taken so that
airline operators can have ease access to financing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
