<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian FM Hopes to Settle S. Leone Crisis Early </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom
Ikimi said today west African countries are hoping to resolve the
crisis in Sierra Leone as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the foreign ministers meeting of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS), Ikimi said review has
been made on the happenings since a military coup overthrew
Sierra eone's legitimate government on May 25.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the review will enable the ECOWAS committee
of four on Sierra Leone, composed of foreign ministers of
Nigeria, Ghana, Guinea and Cote d'Ivoire, to brief the council of
foreign ministers which is scheduled to meet tomorrow in Abuja,
the Nigerian capital.
</P>
<P>
it will also enable the committee "to put together our
recommendations to the heads of state at the ECOWAS summit in
Abuja on August 28 and 29," Ikimi said, quoted by the Nigerian
Television Authority.
</P>
<P>
"We hope our recommendations will indeed include concrete
measures that will be put in place to ensure that the central
objective of ECOWAS, that is to say, the early reinstatement of
Sierra Leone's legitimate government of President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah, has been considered consistently in the past," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Sierra Leonean ambassador to Nigeria was also
quoted as saying he hoped that the ECOWAS heads of state could
resolve the crisis in his country as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
"As long as it (the military junta in power in Sierra Leone)
stays, the Sierra Leoneans suffer," the envoy added.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS, the 16-member sub-regional economic bloc, has faced
with political crisis at all its meetings since 1990 following
the outbreak of Liberia's civil war. It has to dwell largely on
the issue of conflict in one of its member country after another.
</P>
<P>
To date, the Liberian crisis has been resolved once and for
all but the sub-region is facing another crisis in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that the issue will be put high on the
agenda of the coming ECOWAS summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
