<HEADLINE> Ross not Decided to Return to Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- There is no fixed date for
U.S. mediator Dennis Ross to return to the Middle East as Israel
has disclosed, the State Department said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin was responding to a
report that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu had said
Ross intended to travel to the region to follow up on Palestinian
promises to improve security ties with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
"Dennis Ross has made no decision to travel to the region, so
that (report) is not correct," Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
But he assured the reporters at a regular briefing that Ross
will surely accompany Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on her
trip to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Ross "will make a decision about his travel in the context of
the secretary's decision about her travel," Rubin added.
</P>
<P>
Rubin also said reports about her postponement of the Middle
East were "erroneous", saying: "Secretary Albright does intend to
travel to the Middle East very soon."
</P>
<P>
"The prospects for advancing the peace process on that trip
would be advanced if the Palestinian Authority were in a position
to provide additional information (on security matters)...
so that the focus would not be on security, but the focus
could be on restoring the trust and confidence that has been so
unfortunately lost," Rubin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
