<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cigarette Smuggling on the Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The volume of cigarette
smuggling has nearly tripled in the last decade, the New York
Times reported today, citing research data.
</P>
<P>
A total of 280 billion of the 1 trillion cigarettes exported
each year by all producing nations pass through the hands of
smugglers, up from 100 billion in 1989, the paper quoted the
London-based research firm Market Tracking International Ltd. as
saying.
</P>
<P>
One-fourth of the cigarettes sold overseas pass through
smuggling rings set up to evade foreign taxes and sell major
brands at a discount, it added.
</P>
<P>
Recent criminal investigations in several countries show that
big cigarette makers have played a significant role at times in
stimulating the smuggling activity, the Times said.
</P>
<P>
For instance, two organized crime groups in Italy take in 500
million U.S. dollars a year by smuggling in Marlboros they buy
from Swiss dealers selling products made by the Philip Morris
companies, the largest U.S. cigarette maker, it went on.
</P>
<P>
The R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Company, the second largest U.S.
cigarette maker, sponsored trips to a luxury Canadian fishing
resort for several dealers who have since been charged with
conspiring to smuggle cigarettes into Canada, it said.
</P>
<P>
"The rise in smuggling also has coincided with a huge push by
the American companies to expand overseas, which they see as a way
to offset a a decline in sales at home," the paper said, noting
that the smuggling costs foreign governments an estimated 16
billion U.S. dollars a year in lost revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
