<HEADLINE> Ceremony Marks 40th Anniversary of CPCA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 26 (Xinhua) -- A ceremony marking the 40th
anniversary of the Chinese Patriotic Catholic Association (CPCA)
was held in the Great Hall of the People here today.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Qian Qichen, Director of United Front Work
Department of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee
Wang Zhaoguo, Vice-Chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) Zhao
Puchu and a number of other high-ranking leaders attended the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Qian, a member of the Political Bureau of the CPC Central
Committee, extended congratulations to the CPCA on behalf of the
CPC Central Committee and the State Council.
</P>
<P>
He noted insightful Chinese catholics established the Chinese
Patriotic Catholic Association some 40 years ago out of patriotism
and a national sense of justice.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 40 years, the CPCA has extended great effort to
safeguard national sovereignty and dignity, and protect the legal
rights and interests of catholics. The association has contributed
greatly to socialist material development and cultural and ethical
progress.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier expressed that the CPCA will continue to hold
high the banner of patriotism and will continue to unswervingly
and independently seek self-development.
</P>
<P>
Qian also called for the CPCA to conduct religious activities
with the scope of laws, regulations and policies, and to
resolutely resist hostile forces attempting to interfere in the
internal religious affairs of the country and split the motherland
under the pretext of religion.
</P>
<P>
Fu Tieshan, vice-chairman of the CPCA, said Catholics
steadfastly adhere to inheriting and carrying forth the fine
tradition of loving the country and religion and promoting unity
and progress. Catholics continue to hold high the banner of
patriotism and unswervingly and independently seek
self-development. He said Catholics will do everything possible to
safeguard social stability.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was jointly sponsored by the CPCA and the Chinese
Catholic Bishops College. Some 200 representatives from
organizations across the nation attended the ceremony along with
leading officials from relevant departments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
