<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Provides Technical Assistance to Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) has approved two technical assistance (TA) grants worth some
1.1 million U.S. dollars to Nepal for its capital market
development project and rural finance project.
</P>
<P>
While the ADB has provided a similar assistance for the
development of capital market in Nepal, the new TA grant of
596,000 dollars will help examine how to revive and further
develop Nepal's capital market into a more reliable and efficient
mechanism to mobilize savings for growing private investment, said
a press release distributed today by the ADB's resident office in
Kathmandu.
</P>
<P>
The project is aimed at strengthening the monitoring and
enforcement functions of the Securities Board and modernizing the
Nepal Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The ADB has also been extensively involved in the rural finance
sector in Nepal in the past and therefore recognizes that rural
credit is one of the critical inputs for raising the incomes of
the impoverished rural population, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that a number of financial institutions have
been engaged in rural credit delivery, it is estimated that such
formal credit supply covers only about 20 percent of the total
demand, the release noted.
</P>
<P>
Therefor, the ADB will also provide a 500,000 dollar TA grant,
which will be implemented over a period of five months, to assist
Nepal in formulating a Rural Finance Investment Project, said the
press release.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
