<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 900 Million Asians Live in Poverty: World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- As many as 900 million Asians
live in dire poverty despite the fact that Asia's surging growth
has brought the region unprecedented prosperity, the World Bank
said in reports released here today.
</P>
<P>
The reports, entitled "Everyone's Miracle? Revisiting Poverty
and Inequality in East Asia and India: Achievements and Challenges
in Reducing Poverty," described how poverty has fallen
dramatically in East Asia, which is down 27 percent from 1975 to
1985 and a further 35 percent from 1985 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
However, the reports noted that two-thirds of the world's poor
still live in the regions, struggling to live on less than a
dollar a day, which is used by the World Bank as the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that national development cannot be assured
when so many people live without the basic amenities of life, and
lack the means to better themselves.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that poverty has been largely eradicated in
the four "tiger" economies -- Hong Kong of China, South Korea,
Singapore and Taiwan of China -- and has sharply declined in other
countries such as Indonesia and Thailand, as many as 350 million
people are still caught in its grip especially in the new emerging
economies of Cambodia, China, Laos, Mongolia and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
In countries such as China, Indonesia, Malaysia and the
Philippines, where poverty reduction has been more successful, the
reports noted, there is apprehension that there are still millions
who are being left behind as national prosperity rises. Rural
areas have substantially higher incidence of poverty than urban
areas. In some countries, poverty is twice as high in rural areas
than urban.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the World Bank gave a warning of increasingly
widespread inequality.
</P>
<P>
One of the key features of this inequality is the growing gap
in earning power between skilled and unskilled workers in
increasingly sophisticated economies. The bank claimed that across
Asia, the rate of increase of demand for skilled workers has
outstripped the rate of supply, raising earnings differentials
across many occupations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Demand for Durable Goods Drops Again in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Orders for durable goods
fell 0.6 percent in July, the second drop in three months, partly
as a result of slack demand for aircraft and electronic and
communications gear, the Commerce Department reported here today.
</P>
<P>
It said that orders totaled a seasonally adjusted 180.5 billion
U.S. dollars, down from 181.6 billion dollars in June.
</P>
<P>
Orders for durable goods such as trucks and turbines expected
to last more than three years are a major measure of the nation's
manufacturing strength.
</P>
<P>
Despite the decline, analysts say the manufacturing sector
remains healthy.
</P>
<P>
The backlog of unfilled orders slipped 0.6 percent, the first
decline since April. Meanwhile, shipments, a measure of current
demand, rose 1.7 percent, the sixth advance in seven months.
</P>
<P>
Transportation orders slipped 3.5 percent after surging 8.8
percent in June. Declining demand for aircraft more than offset
increased orders for motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the transportation component, orders were up 0.3
percent, the third increase in the last four months.
</P>
<P>
Orders for electronic and other electrical equipment also
dropped, down 13.6 percent after a 2.6 percent dip in June.
</P>
<P>
However, demand for industrial machinery and equipment
increased 5.9 percent on top of June's 1.1 percent advance. And
orders for primary metals rose 3.5 percent, the eighth increase in
nine months.
</P>
<P>
The orders for military equipment fell 6.6 percent after
jumping 13.5 percent a month earlier. Excluding this component,
orders were down 0.4 percent. Orders for nonmilitary capital goods
excluding aircraft rose 5.3 percent, even stronger than June's 3
percent gain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
