<HEADLINE> Illegal-Staying Aliens Urged to Leave Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The Interior Ministry of
Saudi Arabia today urged all foreigners staying illegally in the
kingdom to immediately leave for their home countries or they
would face prison and fines.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a statement carried by Saudi Press News
Agency that the overstayers in the country who will leave
immediately would be pardoned of imprisonment and financial
fines. But it did not give a time limit for them to leave the
country.
</P>
<P>
The statement said those who do not abide by the regulations
concerning illegal staying foreigners would be subject to a
two-year imprisonment and a fine that could be up to 27,000
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Those who mostly violate the regulations are people who arrive
in Saudi Arabia to perform the Muslim pilgrimage ritual,
according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Every year, millions of Muslims from all over the world flock
to the kingdom to perform religious pilgrimage during Haj, but
some of them continue to stay in the country illegally after the
festival.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi authorities launched an organized campaign three
year ago to apprehend those who breaches residence laws and
deport them to their home countries.
</P>
<P>
Before last year's pilgrimage season, the Saudi government
worked out an understanding with other Islamic countries on
applying more disciplined regulations to insure that foreigner
do not stay in the kingdom after performing their rituals.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ministry also warned Saudi citizens and local
companies against employing the violators or assisting them in a
way they could continue their illegal stay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
