<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Claims Link Mad Cow Disease to Water Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Contaminated water supply might
be a source of infection for the brain-wasting Creutzfeldt-Jakob
Disease (CJD), the human counterpart of mad cow disease, The Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Gary Skillet, a former building contractor at Canterbury Mills
rendering the carcasses of slaughtered cattle which may had been
infected with mad cow disease, disclosed that the liquid waste of
the carcasses in the plant was poured down a well.
</P>
<P>
However, David Richardson, director of the mills, denied the
allegation, saying that they had "never put anything down the well
other than rain water."
</P>
<P>
The Canterbury Mills, a rendering plant near Godmersham, is
believed to be the only one in Britain, which spread its effluent
across fields where drinking water is taken.
</P>
<P>
Skillet said the workers at the Canterbury Mills used a well to
get rid of liquid waste from carcasses disposed of under the
government's culling program.
</P>
<P>
The effluent was regularly pumped into the 50-feet-deep well
which links with a water supply system for a large area of east
Kent, where three persons living within 20 miles from the mills
died of new-variant of CJD, he added.
</P>
<P>
Alan Colchester, a consultant neurologist at Guy's Hospital in
London who has treated three of the new-variant CJD cases from
Kent, has already voiced his concern over a possible link with
contaminated water.
</P>
<P>
He said on Monday that he was anxious to know whether effluent
from the rendering process had leaked into the water supply system
because it could be a route of infection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia: More Jobs to Nationals, No to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia today urged
local employers to enlist more nationals and turn away the
expatriates, who account for one-third of the country's
population, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Minister of Labor and Social Affairs Musaid Al-Sinani
said his ministry has notified all departments about the
necessity in this respect, according to Saudi Press Agency.
</P>
<P>
The government has decided that Saudi institutions should
increase employment of nationals by 5 percent per year and reserve
certain jobs for Saudis such as auditing, treasury, civil and
security guarding, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said various departments and sectors are
cooperating with the government to ensure employment priority for
nationals.
</P>
<P>
The country's sixth five-year Development Plan (1995-2000)
calls for the creation of nearly 660,900 jobs for Saudis until the
turn of this century.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia now hosts about 6.5 million foreign workers from
190 countries, mainly from south Asian and Arab states. Saudi
Arabia's population is around 18 million with the expatriates
included.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom decided to stop renewing and issuing work permits
to expatriates in 13 professions in October last year, and in
seven more categories last month.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia and the other member states of the Gulf
Cooperation Council -- Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain,
Oman and Qatar -- are all in a drive to replace foreign workers
with nationals.
</P>
<P>
However, local economists observed that getting rid of foreign
laborers and replacing them with local workers is causing problems
in the job market because the region's education system cannot
cater for the demand of various skills by the private sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
