<HEADLINE> Czech PM Rejects U.S. Allegation on Citizen Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus
has rejected allegations from the U.S. Congress that the country's
Citizen Law was biased, and reiterated that the law would not be
amended.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in response to an open letter addressed to
him last week by two U.S. congressmen that said the Czech
Republic's current Citizen Law is unfair toward Czech Gypsies, or
Roma, as they preferred to be called, and should be revised.
</P>
<P>
The allegations stem from the current wave of emigration of
Czech Roma who seek permanent residence in Canada.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Czech citizens do not need visas to visit
Canada, so Roma simply apply for residence or refugee status once
they reach Canada.
</P>
<P>
But Klaus said recently that he didn't expect Canada to accept
Czech Roma and discouraged mass emigration.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 200,000 ethnic Roma live in the Czech Republic
now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
