<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Lower House to Debate Charter Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine House of
Representatives is scheduled to open debate Wednesday on whether
to turn the bicameral congress into a constituent assembly in
order to amend the constitution.
</P>
<P>
Pedro Romualdo, chairman of the House Committee on
Constitutional Amendments, said today he is ready to present
Wednesday the resolution on converting Congress to a constituent
assembly on the floor.
</P>
<P>
Romualdo, a principal proponent for the resolution, said he
will deliver a sponsorship speech to defend the bill Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Jose de Venecia, a proclaimed presidential
aspirant for the 1998 elections, said today that he had started a
series of caucus among the ruling party's congress group to get
their pulse on the resolution.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference this afternoon, de Venecia, general
secretary of the ruling Lakas-NUCD Party, disclosed that he had
already met with the party's Visayan bloc Monday night.
</P>
<P>
He said that a majority of the party's congressmen from the
Visayas region are in favor of the approval of House Concurrent
Resolution 40 on the creation of a constituent assembly.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, the battlefield for changing the 1987
constitution moved to Congress as the supporters of President
Fidel Ramos in the legislative body pushed hard for opening a
debate on the charter change issue.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the country's Commission on Election rejected a
petition by Ramos' supporters to verify millions of signatures
they gathered for holding a referendum to amend the charter.
</P>
<P>
Ramos' supporters have sought to rewrite the country's 1987
constitution to lift term limits of all government elective
officials including Ramos before the May 1998 presidential polls.
</P>
<P>
Reportedly, about 138 of the 220 congressmen, including those
from the opposition, will vote for convening Congress into a
constituent assembly since many of them can also extend their
terms of office by changing the charter.
</P>
<P>
But the resolution is expected to meet strong opposition in the
Senate, where the opposition camp enjoyed an overwhelming
majority, after it is carried by the lower house.
</P>
<P>
Senate President Ernesto Maceda, chief of the opposition
Nationalist People's Coalition party, expressed his confidence
today that Resolution 40 will be easily killed since at least 17
of the 24 senate members are expected to vote against it.
</P>
</TEXT>
