<HEADLINE> Economists Forecast 6.5 percent Growth for Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Economists of Standard Charted
Bank, one of the three note-issuing banks in Hong Kong, forecast
a 6.5 percent GDP growth for Hong Kong this year, higher than the
general prediction of about 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The August issue of the bank's "Greater China Viewpoints" says
that economic growth in the first half of 1997 should be higher
than six percent and prospects for the second half remain good.
</P>
<P>
Growth in consumption is picking up and investment is gaining
momentum in Hong Kong, reflecting strong confidence on the
economy, according to the monthly report. Optimism about Hong
Kong's economic prospects partly comes from the view that China's
economy will continue to do well.
</P>
<P>
The report also predicts that major stock market corrections
are unlikely to affect the overall performance of Hong Kong's
economy.
</P>
<P>
As to concern that the currency turmoil in Southeast Asia might
spill over to Hong Kong, the bank's report says that confidence
in Hong Kong dollar remains strong and speculators will find it
very difficult to undermine confidence in the local currency.
</P>
</TEXT>
