<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Reactor Construction in DPRK Possibly Takes More Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Construction of two light-water
nuclear reactors in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea,
originally set for completion in 2003, will take at least two
years longer, said the president of the project's prime contractor
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Establishing a nuclear reactor requires at least 95 months -
even if construction goes favorably - while it takes at least 107
months to build two reactors using advanced South Korean
techniques," said Rieh Chong-hun, president of the state-run South
Korean Electric Company.
</P>
<P>
Under a DPRK-U.S. accord, the U.S.-led multinational consortium
of Korean Peninsula Energy Development Organization (KEDO) will
provide the two units of pressurized water reactors, in exchange
for DPRK's freezing its own nuclear program which is more capable
of producing weapon-grade plutonium.
</P>
<P>
"If we get main orders to build the 1,000-megawatt nuclear
reactors in January next year, we could finish building the first
reactor in 2005, while the second one will be completed by 2006,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The groundbreaking ceremony for the main construction is
expected to be held next year, said Rieh, who returned to Seoul
after attending a ceremony marking the start of construction of
basic facilities in Sinpo, DPRK, on August 19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
