<BODY>
<HEADLINE> De Klerk to Be Offered Honorary Position After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 26 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's National
Party Leader FW de Klerk will be offered the newly-created
position of honorary president of the party when he retires from
the leadership.
</P>
<P>
The opposition National Party has decided to recommend a
constitutional amendment to the Federal Council, which will allow
for an honorary president for FW de Klerk, the party's executive
said today.
</P>
<P>
After the election of the new leader, the Federal Council
will, should the recommednation be accepted, offer honorary
position to de Klerk, the excutive said.
</P>
<P>
De Klerk announced at a press conference in Cape Town today
that he will quit politics after 25 years of service.
</P>
<P>
The National Party is to elect its new leader on September 9
at a meeting of its electoral college in Cape Town, South African
Press Association quoted National Party sources as reporting.
</P>
<P>
De Klerk said that a new party leader should be given ample
opportunity to establish himself or herself before the 1999
general elections and to lead the National Party through the
process of realignment and cooperation with other parties.
</P>
<P>
De Klerk said he will remain the party leader until then and
will resign shortly afterwards as member of parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
