<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Report Stresses Critical Role of Energy in Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 26 (Xinhua) -- UNDP released a report entitled
"Energy After Rio: Prospects and Challenges" here today, which
discusses energy's critical link to poverty and development.
</P>
<P>
"Energy is directly related to the most pressing social issues
which affect sustainable development", says the report.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that this report can serve to highlight the critical
importance of energy to sustainable development and the reality
that current patterns of energy production and use in most
countries of the world are unsustainable", says Arthur N. Holcome,
UNDP Resident Representative in China, at today's press conference.
</P>
<P>
The report shows that more than 1.5 billion people today lack
access to electricity, and tow billion people use traditional
fuels such as firewood and animal dung for cooking.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the heavy dependence on imported
fossil fuels has led to foreign debt problems in the developing
world. Investments in alternative energy technologies that require
lower expenditures of foreign exchange earnings would release
capital for other development needs.
</P>
<P>
The report says that increased access to energy is essential
to providing improved health care, education, housing, water and
sanitation services for people living in poverty. In particular,
women will benefit from modern energy.
</P>
<P>
Recent technological advances offer great prospects for
developing sustainable energy systems and developing countries
today have the opportunity to leapfrog to modern technologies, the
report states.
</P>
<P>
Annual energy investment requirements worldwide are projected
to rise to 750 billion US dollars by 2020, up from 450 billion US
dollars in the mid-1990s. Renewable and higher efficiency energy
systems would enable developing countries to meet growing needs at
a lower cost, says the report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
