<HEADLINE> Georgian Parliamentary Official Stresses Ties With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIBILISI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- A senior Georgian parliamentary
official said today the visit by a delegation of the Chinese
National People's Congress (NPC) promoted understanding between
the two countries' parliaments and boosted overall bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Eldar Shengelaia, deputy speaker of the National Assembly
(parliament) of Georgia, made the remarks as he saw the Chinese
NPC delegation off at the airport.
</P>
<P>
Shengelaia said that relations between Georgia and China have
developed rapidly since they established diplomatic ties in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Frequent contacts between leaders of the two countries had
established a good basis for bilateral ties and Georgia had had
great support from China since it declared independence in 1991,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He hailed the achievements China made in its reform and opening
up, adding Georgia can learn a lot from China's success.
</P>
<P>
Shengelaia said China's successful resumption of the exercise
of sovereignty over Hong Kong has also set a very good example for
Georgia in solving similar problems.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation, led by Vice-Chairman of the NPC
Standing Committee Wang Bingqian, visited the Transcaucasus
country from August 21-25. The delegation met with Georgian
President Eduard Shervardnadze and Speaker of the National
Assembly of Georgia Zurab Zhvaniya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
