<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Experts Predict Booming State Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Professor Huang Da, a
well-known Chinese economist, claims that the time has come for
the state economy to rid itself of loss-making state-owned
enterprises due to the rapid growth of non-state economic sectors.
</P>
<P>
In an address to the ongoing Ninth Annual PACAP Finance
Conference, Huang, chairman of China Financial Institute, said
that non-state sectors have played a balancing role in China's
national economy, a role somewhat different than that of the state
sector.
</P>
<P>
"This has created a rare opportunity for state-owned
enterprises to cast aside their embarrassing record of economic
performance," said Huang.
</P>
<P>
The increasing pressure China is facing both at home and abroad
is driving the country to accelerate financial reform.
</P>
<P>
"However, China should 'not act in haste,' but should instead
follow its own approach in reforming the state sector, rather than
simply copying the international practice, said Huang.
</P>
<P>
He said that appropriate attention should be placed on
reexamining the role state-owned enterprises play in the national
economy, and China must properly handle the relationships between
reform, development, and stability of the financial market.
</P>
<P>
Huang pointed out that state-owned enterprises have become de
facto "taxpayers" shouldering the heavy costs of the nation's
economic reform.
</P>
<P>
He praised the state-owned enterprises for their shouldering
the responsibility of ensuring social stability. This, he added,
has laid a solid foundation for the rapid development of national
economy.
</P>
<P>
He urged non-state sectors to pay for the country's development
along with the state-owned sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
