<HEADLINE> Russia Denies Helping Iran With Missile Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Russia has categorically denied
media reports that it is helping Iran develop ballistic missiles,
the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Israeli television on Sunday alleged that Russia had been
helping Iran develop guidance and delivery systems for long-range
missiles and had provided Iran with the know-how to make warheads.
</P>
<P>
The television also said hundreds of Russian scientists were
working on the Iranian project.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that U.S. State Department spokesman James
Rubin said that Washington was taking the reports of Russian aid
for Iranian missile programs "very seriously".
</P>
<P>
Interfax quoted a Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman as saying
Tuesday that Russia has "provided the Americans and the Israelis
with numerous explanations on this issue".
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu sent Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov a strongly-worded message last Thursday
protesting Russia's alleged missile cooperation with the Islamic
republic.
</P>
<P>
The press service of the Russian Foreign Intelligence Service
said reports of Russian involvement in the Iranian missile program
were "absolutely groundless".
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu last Friday called a cabinet meeting, which proposed
freezing major economic cooperation projects with Russia, such as
the import of Russian natural gas, if Moscow continued to help
Iran develop the missiles.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Iran in April signed an agreement on export
restrictions which the Russian Foreign Ministry described as
"confirmation that both nations are committed to the norms of the
nonproliferation of weapons of mass destruction and their means of
delivery." 
</P>
</TEXT>
