<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Deploy Warplanes in Bahrain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States will deploy
some warplanes in Bahrain in the next few months, Bahrain's
Foreign Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The Bahrain News Agency quoted the ministry said saying in a
statement that Bahrain has granted the U.S. to deploy "a team of
planes" in the Gulf island state.
</P>
<P>
The deployment will begin from September 19 and last till
October 20, the statement said, adding it came within the
framework of a U.S.-Bahraini defense treaty singed after the 1991
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The statement gave no further details about the coming
deployment, but western diplomats here said the movement is part
of U.S. efforts to support NATO's Operation Southern Watch, which
was launched to uphold international sanctions imposed on Iraq
since Iraqi invasion against Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
They also said the planes are likely from the U.S. Air
Expeditionary Force (AEF), a light and lean package of aircraft
and personnel designed to deploy to a forward location and
immediately employ combat assets.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time for the U.S. to deploy warplanes
in the Gulf region this year. The U.S. made the first one
in Qatar during the period from February 30 to May 20 when
some 30 fighters and more than 1,000 airmen were sent there.
</P>
</TEXT>
