<HEADLINE> UN to Reduce Budget for Palestinian Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Some 7 million U.S. dollars used
for the social welfare of Palestinian refugees will be chopped
from the 1997 budget of the United Nations Relief and Works
BDH231WSB017S26PEQL22:0922:101322
Agency (UNRWA), a Lebanese newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Start quoted Lebanese Foreign Minister Fares Boueiz
as saying that the reason is the lack of contributions from donor
nations.
</P>
<P>
The director of UNRWA in Lebanon, Lionel Brisson, delivered
a letter Monday to Boueiz, informing him of the reduction in
this year's budget of 54.7 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz criticized the timing of the decrease in the UNRWA
budget, saying it was an attempt to pressure Lebanon into
accepting certain conditions for peace.
</P>
<P>
"The donor countries have decided to cut back on their
funding. This will have serious repercussions on the education
and medical coverage of the Palestinian refugees in Lebanon,"
Boueiz said at a news conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
The UNRWA was set up in 1950 to care for the social welfare
of the Palestinians in refugee camps. Of the 3.3 million
Palestinian refugees depending on the agency's aid, 360,000
reside in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The refugees in Lebanon are classified as "temporary
residents" and do not benefit from government services. They
rely largely on the UNRWA for schooling, health care and
camp infrastructure construction.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz insisted that the plight of the Palestinian refugees
was the responsibility of the international community and should
not be shouldered solely by the host countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
