<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Model of Using Tobacco Tax to Control Smoking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 26 (Xinhua) -- An Australian organization today
urged all countries in the world to consider a new model of using
tobacco tax in health promotion and smoking control.
</P>
<P>
The model, created by the Australian Victorian Health Promotion
Foundation (VicHealth), can help governments to secure long-term
funding for smoking control from a tobacco tax without claiming
funds from the general health budget, the 10th World Conference on
Tobacco or Health was told in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
"Taxing tobacco, which increases the price of cigarettes, is in
itself a disincentive for many people to continue smoking and for
young people to take up smoking," Ms Rhonda Galbally, Chief
Executive-Officer of VicHealth explained.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, using tobacco tax in tobacco control can help many
countries to settle the problem of fund shortage in health
promotion programs," she added.
</P>
<P>
The model has already produced positive effect on people's
health in Australia, and many countries have followed suit to
apply the model in one form or another, she said.
</P>
<P>
"China, the biggest tobacco producer and consumer in the world,
may make a good reference out of the model," said Cai Renhua,
Director of the Health Policy and Law Department of the Chinese
Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
The tobacco industry has been a major source for China's
revenue since 1987. It turned out 83 billion yuan (about 10
billion US dollars) in revenue in 1996, five times that of 1986,
according to a report from the Chinese Academy of Preventive
Medicine (CAPM).
</P>
<P>
The medical expenses on tobacco-related diseases accounted for
13 percent of the total in China in 1993, said Prof. Jin Shuigao
from the CAPM during a symposia of the conference.
</P>
<P>
He said that the direct expenses on tobacco throughout the
country are estimated to double for every 3.5 years during the
1989-2000 period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
