<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bundesbank Leaves Repurchase Rate Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The German central bank decided
today to leave its weekly securities repurchase rate unchanged at
3.0 percent despite earlier projections of rising inflation in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Speculations about a rate hike by the Bundesbank gained force
on Monday after the German federal statistics office in Wiesbaden
warned that the inflation rate in western Germany would top 2.0
percent in August.
</P>
<P>
Although many analysts in Frankfurt predicted that the
Bundesbank might move to raise the repurchase rate a little bit in
the near future, they also agreed that the current weakness of the
U.S. dollar against the German mark had apparently given the
Bundesbank some reasons to take a wait-and-see attitude for the
moment.
</P>
<P>
A rate hike by the Bundesbank carries the risk of choking the
much-needed economic growth in Germany and undermine the
government's efforts to reduce record unemployment of over 11
percent.
</P>
<P>
In a separate development, the German umbrella group of
chambers of commerce DIHT today called on the government to curb
public spendings as a means of easing inflationary pressures in
the economy.
</P>
<P>
DIHT chief economist Guenter Albrecht told the German Saar
Radio that he hoped inflation could be held below 2 percent, since
a rise in inflation rates "would not be good for the economy".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
