<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Urges Expanded Water Conservancy Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Jiang
Chunyun has urged various localities to earnestly summarize their
experience in fighting disasters and accelerate the construction
of water conservancy projects.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, a member of the Political Bureau of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC), conducted a
agricultural fact-finding tour in northeast China's Jilin Province
between August 22-26, and attended a Changchun agricultural
symposium sponsored jointly by Liaoning, Jilin and Heilongjiang
provinces and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier surveyed the production of farm crops,
inspected a group of pillar agricultural enterprises, and visited
village and rural households affected by the severe drought.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that Jilin has suffered from a prolonged severe
drought this year. However, he noted that losses have been greatly
reduced due to the adoption of effective measures and strenuous
efforts of local authorities and people.
</P>
<P>
He urged various localities to place the highest priority on
processing and marketing agricultural products, and on
accelerating the industrialization of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
He said that Liaoning, Jilin, Heilongjiang and Inner Mongolia
are the country's major grain producers, and as such will play
decisive roles in ensuring the nation's grain supply.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier urged the localities to earnestly draw on
experience and lessons learned from the drought disaster and
recognize the importance and urgency of the irrigation and water
conservancy construction.
</P>
<P>
He also called for local authorities to pay close attention to
afforestation, the development of agricultural science and
technology, and diversified agricultural management.
</P>
<P>
According to Wu, local authorities should give full play to the
initiative of farmers and adopt effective measures to relieve
their burdens.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier urged various localities to prioritize
material development and cultural and ethical progress to promote
coordinated economic and social development in rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
