<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Device Using Sounds Developed to Help Blind </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 26 (Xinhua) -- British scientists have developed
a device using musical sounds to help blind people to find their
way around, The Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The researchers believe that blind or partially sighted people
can be trained to visualize scenes and objects such as houses and
trees if they are described in sound patterns, or "auditory
fingerprints".
</P>
<P>
The research team, which is supported by the Government's
Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council, is planning to
develop a prototype system called an optophone.
</P>
<P>
It will consist of a portable computer that can process images
into sounds, linked to glasses with in-built cameras and
headphones.
</P>
<P>
A team at Nene College, Northampton, led by Phil Picton, is
running the three- year project.
</P>
<P>
"The aim is to develop a prototype device capable of turning
moving images into sounds in real time," a spokesman for the
research council said.
</P>
<P>
Picton plans to use volunteers, some sighted and some visually
impaired, to test whether the brain can form pictures from sounds.
</P>
<P>
The optophone system is initially being developed to scan black
and white images. Picton has developed a computer software program
that translates the images into different harmonics.
</P>
<P>
The next stage is to see if the system can use sounds to
distinguish between the elements in moving color pictures. It is
hoped that objects will have their own sounds that can be learnt
and recognized by blind users. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
