<HEADLINE> Former S. African President Declares Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
president F. W. De Klerk announced in Cape Town today that he
will quit politics after 25 years of service.
</P>
<P>
De Klerk, leader of South African opposition National Party,
told a press conference that "after careful consideration, I have
decided that the time has come for me to retire from active
politics."
</P>
<P>
He denied allegation that his decision to quit politics is
relevant to disputes with the Truth and Reconciliation Commission
(TRC), a fact-finding group authorized by the government to
investigate violent activities during the apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
"I am retiring because I am convinced it is in the best
interest of the party and the country," the South African Press
Association quoted De Klerk as reporting.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the coming 1999 elections make it necessary
that a change in leadership will take place timeously to allow
a new leader to establish and prove himself.
</P>
<P>
De Klerk said there is a urgent need for political
realignment in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"With my retirement I wish to open a door for the National
Party to provide further proof of its dynamic break with the
past, with a view to best enabling it to play its full role in
the realignment process," he said.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to National Party members to give their new leader
a chance and to continue to work for a party that could make a
difference.
</P>
<P>
De Klerk said he remains committed to everything which the
new National Party stands for and will continue to promote these
goals after his retirement, both inside the country and overseas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
