<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laos, Myanmar Agree to Visa Exemption for ASEAN Nationals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 26 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN Secretary-General
Ajit Singh said here today that Laos and Myanmar, the two new
members of the grouping, have agreed to introduce visa-free entry
for ASEAN nationals by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
Both countries, which joined ASEAN (the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations) last month, gave the commitment at the
Second Meeting of ASEAN Heads of Immigration Department, Ajit
Singh told reporters after the conclusion of the two-day meeting
here.
</P>
<P>
"Vietnam, which joined ASEAN in 1995, said they'll have to look
into some technical and administrative matters, but they have
assured us that they too will try to meet this deadline," the
ASEAN chief said.
</P>
<P>
Visas are not required currently in the other six ASEAN members
-- Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, the Philippines and
Thailand -- for a length of stay of one month.
</P>
<P>
Ajit Singh said on the establishment of ASEAN lanes at
international airports of ASEAN members, Laos and the Philippines
agreed to implement immediately.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar introduced the system just before its officials came to
Kuala Lumpur to attend the meeting while Malaysia would see its
ASEAN lanes at the new Kuala Lumpur International Airport in
Sepang when it commences commercial operations in the first
quarter of next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Brunei and Singapore will also look into the matter," he said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand and Indonesia have already established the lanes in
their airports.
</P>
<P>
Such lanes will speed up immigration clearance for ASEAN
nationals visiting a member country, Ajit Singh said.
</P>
<P>
On the proposal to introduce smart cards to facilitate
intra-ASEAN travel, Ajit Singh said the meeting agreed to set up
a technical working group led by Indonesia to study the matter.
</P>
<P>
He said the group was also tasked to look into the
standardization of immigration disembarkation cards especially in
light of the smart-card proposal.
</P>
<P>
He said the older six ASEAN members also agreed to help train
immigration officers from Laos, Myanmar and Vietnam with funding
from the Jakarta-based ASEAN Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The next meeting of ASEAN immigration and consular division
chiefs will be held in Myanmar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
