</P>
<P>
Reporting to the ongoing 27th Standing Committee Meeting of
the National People's Congress here today, Director of National
Meteorological Bureau Wen Kegang said that China now has a
comprehensive meteorological monitoring system, with about 2,600
meteorological stations across the country.
</P>
<P>
The national and regional meteorological centers are
computerized, and meteorological stations at provincial and city
levels can make short and middle-term weather forecasts with
rather high accuracy.
</P>
<P>
"China leads the developing countries in the meteorological
technology and in some aspects is catching up with that of the
world developed countries in the 1990s," Wen told the lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, China is relatively weak in climate monitoring
and forecasts, especially in short-term climate
forecasts. Climate-related natural disasters have caused the country
a loss of grain output averaging 15 billion kilograms per year.
</P>
<P>
Wen pledged to enhance climate research and meanwhile increase
investment in meteorological satellites development projects and
its application technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
