<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Examine Draft Price Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 26 (Xinhua) -- China's draft Price Law
submitted to the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress on Monday has triggered lively discussion amongst
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
Members of the NPC Standing Committee noted that a price law is
extremely necessary at a time when China is advancing towards its
market-oriented economy. Such a law, they pointed out, will not
only check illegal pricing activities, but will also promote price
reform.
</P>
<P>
A number of committee members said that a reasonable pricing
system not only touches the life of all people, but also has a
direct bearing on national economy and social stability. They
suggested "the use of reasonable pricing to create a fair
competitive environment" and "safeguard the legal rights of both
traders and consumers" should be written into the general
principles of the law.
</P>
<P>
The draft law stipulates three forms of pricing: prices
determined by market competition; government-set prices; and
prices subject to government guidelines.
</P>
<P>
Noted economist Dong Furen said the law should contain explicit
wording on government activities in order to eliminate
inappropriate official interference. For example, the scope of
government-set prices and prices subject to government guidelines
should be clearly defined.
</P>
<P>
According to Dong, the draft seems to allocate too much power
to price management departments, including a clause permitting
said departments to investigate the saving deposits of legal
entities and audit accounting records.
</P>
<P>
Dong cautioned that the law should define and restrict such
activities to ensure smooth operation of the market.
</P>
<P>
NPC Standing Committee members criticised irregularities in
pricing system and suggested that the law underscore the
protection of consumers interests and include articles preventing
excessive profit-making activities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
