<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Passive Smokers Suffer from Serious Hazards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The latest survey shows that
second-hand "smoking" is closely related to the incidence of heart
diseases and lung cancer and can seriously damage children's
health.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 10th World Conference on Tobacco or Health,
Dr. Stanton Glantz from the University of California said that a
large number of epidemiological studies showed that an increase of
around 30 percent in the risk of cardio-vascular diseases were
related with being married to a smoker.
</P>
<P>
He said that second-hand smoke exposure can first cause damage
to the cardio-vascular system, which results in about 50,000 to
60,000 annual deaths in the United States.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 surveys, carried out in China, Japan, the United
States, Greek, Britain, Sweden and Russia also found that lifelong
nonsmoking women, living with a smoking spouse, have an estimated
35 percent increase in the risk of lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
The surveys also revealed that in western countries, about 20
to 30 percent of lung cancer cases among nonsmokers are caused by
environmental smoking (ETS).
</P>
<P>
A recent report of the US Environmental Protection Agency said
ETS is responsible for at least 3,000 cases of lung cancer death
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Jonathan Samet from the Johns Hopkins University said that
fetal exposure through maternal smoking is associated with
increased rates of spontaneous abortion and prenatal mortality,
and can reduce infants' birth weight. It could also have lasting
adverse effect on children's growth.
</P>
<P>
He said the involuntary smoking after birth can hinder the
growth of lung during childhood and raise the incidence of
respiratory diseases among children.
</P>
<P>
Parental smoking is also one of the causes for asthma, the most
common chronic disease of childhood, according to the latest
information.
</P>
<P>
Samet noted that the prevention of children's diseases from
passive smoking should focus on the home, while schools are also
required to be smoke-free, and the teachers, not smoke in front of
their students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
