<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourist Arrivals to Macao Drop 4.72 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals to Macao dropped
4.72 percent in the first six months of this year from the same
1996 period, latest statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Macao Census and statistics Department
show that the number of tourists coming to Macao between January
and June reached 3.76 million, a decrease of more than 180,000
from the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The number of Hong Kong visitors, the dominant source of
tourists to Macao, declined by the largest margin of 14.28
percent. That translates to more than 375,000 travelers.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists from Southeast Asian nations also
dropped. In particular, over 20 percent fewer Singaporeans visited
 Macao in the first six months.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, tourist arrivals from Taiwan soared by more than
180,000, to reach 485,300, up 60.29 percent. The number of
tourists from China's inland areas rose 11.3 percent, and tourist
arrivals from Europe also grew 16.22 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the increase of Taiwanese tourists to Macao
is mainly the result of the quasi-direct flights across the Taiwan
Straits. Many Taiwanese tourists and businessmen like to fly to
inland areas via Macao.
</P>
<P>
However, they say that the rising triad-related crimes in Macao
over the past few months have frightened away tourists. But for
the increase of Taiwanese travelers, the number of tourists would
have dropped further.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is a leading source of income for the tiny territory of
some 420,000 residents. The tourism sector and casinos contribute
about half of local revenues.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists to Macao reached 8.15 million last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
