<TEXT>
<P>
PRETORIA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- United Nations special envoy
Jamsheed Marker said here today that South African president
Nelson Mandela's role in the East Timorese conflict had boosted
peace efforts in that region.
</P>
<P>
"Your contribution has been both timely and important. It has
given great impetus to our work in the U.N.," Marker said after
meeting Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Marker, special envoy for East Timor, said the U.N. would
maintain close contact with South Africa in its bid to broker a
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Marker arrived here today for a short visit on the invitation
of Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said he had briefed Marker on his recent talks with
jailed East Timorese rebel leader Xanana Gusmao, Indonesian
president Suharto, and other leading figures involved.
</P>
<P>
Mandela met Gusmao in Jakarta last month during an official
visit to Indonesia. The talks were arranged with the blessing of
Suharto.
</P>
<P>
Mandela called for the release of Gusmao in July, saying all
political leaders in East Timor "had to be free to normalise the
situation".
</P>
<P>
He told reporters today that he had not yet received any
direct response to his appeal. He said his initiatives were in
support of U.N. secretary-general Kofi Annan's strive to promote
international peace.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said Annan has sent Marker to get a direct report from
him on this effort.
</P>
<P>
Gusmao is the leader of East Timorese independent movement. He
was captured in 1992 by Indonesian government and sentenced to 20
years in prison. 
</P>
