<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss UBS Bank Buys Germany's Private Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FRANKFURT, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Switzerland's UBS bank
announced here today that it is taking over majority ownership of
a German private bank from Britain's banking group Lloyds TSB for
about 193 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Lloyds TSB is transferring its entire holding
of more than 75 percent of Germany's Schroeder, Muenchmeyer Hengst
&AMP; Co (SMH) bank to the UBS, Switzerland's largest bank.
</P>
<P>
The Frankfurt-based SMH, which recently switched strategy to
concentrate on investment, was formed in 1969 in a merger of three
German private banks and was bought by the British bank in 1984.
</P>
<P>
The Lloyds TSB said it had decided on the deal because the SMH
no longer fit in with its overall business strategy.
</P>
<P>
The UBS meanwhile said the acquisition was intended to boost
its own position in Germany, the largest continental European
financial market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
