<HEADLINE> Chemical Weapons Agency Chief Meets Dutch PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Jose Bustani, director-general
of the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons
(OPCW), met Dutch Prime Minister Willem Kok Sunday to extend
gratitude for the Dutch hosting to the OPCW headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The OPCW chief also updated the Dutch prime minister about the
latest progress of international inspections and other
implementation activities of Chemical Weapons Convention,
according to an OPCW press release received here today.
</P>
<P>
The convention bans the production, stockpiling and use of
chemical weapons, and provides for the destruction of existing
stocks and production facilities.
</P>
<P>
Bustani and Kok agreed that all member states of the OPCW
convention should pay their financial contributions to the
organization as early as possible so as to ensure that inspection
activities will continue uninterrupted.
</P>
<P>
The OPCW has scheduled to inspect 35 places in August to verify
the implementation of the convention.
</P>
<P>
A total of 98 countries and regions have so far ratified or
acceded to the convention while The Hague-based OPCW is waiting
for another 69 countries and regions, which have signed the
convention, to ratify it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
