<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Manufacturing Industry Hit by Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's manufacturing industry
is facing a dim prospect because of smuggled goods and subsidized
imports, Financial Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Association of Chambers of Commerce and Industry
(ZACCI) warned in its 1997 economic report for the second quarter
that "unless government puts in place anti-dumping duties or
safeguard measures to protect local industry, the country will be
faced with prospects of de-industrialization."
</P>
<P>
ZACCI said dumping cases are very prominent, particularly,
with regard to imported tyres, batteries and other goods that
should push government into putting corrective measures in place
before it is too late.
</P>
<P>
It noted in the report that ZACCI and the Zambia Association
of Manufacturers should double their efforts in reviving the "buy
Zambian" campaign.
</P>
<P>
It said that although the campaign is costly, it will be worth
spending whatever amounts there is as this will benefit the
industry and the country.
</P>
<P>
Last year the sector grew by about 2.5 percent and contributed
almost 29 percent of the total Gross Domestic Product (GDP) of
Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
