<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Trade Surplus Surges in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Germany's trade surplus rose
sharply to 13.4 billion marks (7.34 billion U.S. dollars) in June
from 9.8 billion (5.4 billion dollars) in May and just 6.5 billion
(3.6 billion dollars) last June, the federal statistics office
announced today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Wiesbaden-based office, Germany's exports
surged 23.3 percent in June in year-on-year terms and imports were
up 13.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the massive expansion in visible trade surplus,
Germany's current account balance also swung into a surplus of 4.0
billion marks (2.2 billion dollars) in June, compared with the
deficits of 2.6 billion marks (1.4 billion dollars) in May and 0.8
billion marks (438 million dollars) last June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
