<HEADLINE> China, Kazakhstan Start to Set Up Boundary Markers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- China and Kazakhstan held a
ceremony Sunday for setting up boundary markers at the Alataw
Shankou on the Sino-Kazakh border, the Kazakh news agency reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the Sino-Kazakh Border Agreement signed in 1994, the two
countries are carrying out the work of border demarcation.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the Joint Border Survey Commission of China and
Kazakhstan agreed that the two sides would set up 502 boundary
markers on their 1,700-kilometer-long border, with Kazakhstan and
China having 254 and 248 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The number of the boundary markers is counted from the junction
of China, Kazakhstan and Russia. The boundary markers set up by
Kazakhstan and China on Sunday were No.280 and No.281 separately.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the Chinese and Kazakh frontier forces
attending the ceremony said that choosing the Alataw Shankou as
the place to set up boundary markers for the first time has shown
the developing friendship between China and Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are expected to complete the border
demarcation in 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
