<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng met
here today with Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew of Singapore and the
two leaders expressed their satisfaction over the development of
friendly cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng highly appreciated the rapid development of relations
between China and Singapore in the past several years since the
two countries established diplomatic ties in 1990.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Senior Minister Lee has made great efforts to
promote the bilateral cooperation, which, he said, China will
never forget. He invited Lee Kuan Yew to visit China more often
when convenient.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng also briefed Lee on the smooth operation of the
government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)
since its establishment last month.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese government will fully respect the
high-degree autonomy enjoyed by the Hong Kong SAR, and will make
further efforts to maintain Hong Kong's prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, being an international trade, financial and
transportation center, will continue to contribute to the
prosperity of the Asia-Pacific region, he said.
</P>
<P>
Lee Kuan Yew, reviewing the development of the bilateral
relations, said that he was satisfied with the cooperation between
Singapore and China in all fields. He said Singapore is willing to
continue to strengthen its long-term cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
He also said that he was glad to see Sino-U.S, relations
improving. A stable Sino-U.S. relationship will exert positive
impact on the stability in the Asia-Pacific region, he said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also exchanged views on the financial situation
in Southeast Asia and other issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng concluded his three-day official visit to Singapore
after his meeting with Senior Minister Lee and left for home this
afternoon, winding up his two-nation Southeast Asian tour which
also brought him to Malaysia last week.  
</P>
