<HEADLINE> Japan to Set up Office for Disposal of Chemical Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government decided
today to set up an office as early as October in the cabinet
secretariat to expedite the disposal of chemical weapons left
behind in China by the Japanese troops at the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
The government set up a liaison conference today to handle
coordination among the ministries and agencies involved in
disposing of the poison-gas shells, Chief Cabinet Secretary
Seiroku Kajiyama told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference, headed by Deputy Chief Cabinet Secretary
Teijiro Furukawa, consists of chiefs from the Cabinet Councillor's
Office on External Affairs, the Foreign Ministry, the Finance
Ministry, the Health and Welfare Ministry and the International
Trade and Industry Ministry as well as the agencies of defense,
science and technology and environment.
</P>
<P>
The move is aimed at ensuring united government efforts to
dispose of chemical weapons in line with the spirit of the
Sino-Japanese Joint Declaration, the Sino-Japanese Peace and
Friendship Treaty and the Chemical Weapons Convention, Kajiyama
said.
</P>
<P>
China and Japan have agreed to speed up the disposal of
chemical weapons this year, the 25th anniversary of the
normalization of diplomatic relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 2 million poison-gas shells have been left in
China by the Japanese troops, most of which are in China's
northeastern provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
