<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's External Debt Service Ratio Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's external debt service
ratio has dropped to 22 percent of its total export earnings
reflecting an increase in export earnings and the benefits the
country is drawing from both the multilateral and bilateral
donors.
</P>
<P>
In 1995-1996, the claim of external debt services on export
earnings was 32 percent, according to statistics of the finance
ministry.
</P>
<P>
The reduction of the debt services reflects an expected 10
percent increase in export earnings as well as the declining
trend of the country's debt service payments.
</P>
<P>
In absolute terms, therefore, its net external debt services
come down from 377 million U.S. dollars in 1995 to an expected
259 million dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
But debt services, both external and domestic, have been the
major consumer of the foreign exchange earnings of Zambia in the
first six months of this year as 53 percent of its total inflows
of about 132 million dollars went to service the debts.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from the Bank of Zambia, during the
first quarter, foreign exchange outflows from the central bank
amounted to 72.133 million dollars of which 42.275 million
dollars went to service government debts.
</P>
<P>
The central bank released only 6.9 million dollars on to the
open market and used 11.524 million dollars on other government
uses while non governmentt users consumed 11.22 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Both the inflows and outflows increased further by the end of
June that resulted in the recorded surplus.
</P>
<P>
This has been attributed to the reduction in debt service
ratio following the good performance of the country on the
macroeconomic level and under its structural adjustment program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
