<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former S. African President De Klerk to Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 26 (Xinhua) -- South African opposition
National Party leader FW de Klerk will announce resignation from
his position and departure from politics today, South African
Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted the Cape Town Africans Daily Die Burger as
reporting that De Klerk had informed his deputy leaders in nine
provinces that he would formally resign Tuesday to make place for
a new party leader.
</P>
<P>
De Klerk had not given full reasons for the step, and the nine
leaders had been caught by surprise, the report said.
</P>
<P>
For now, De Klerk spokesman Fanus Schoeman declined to confirm
the report.
</P>
<P>
Although De Klerk has not yet announced his resignation,
leaders of South African parties have voiced their comments over
the matter.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela said in Pretoria today
that he hoped South Africa would remember the role De Klerk had
played in bringing about a peaceful political transformation in
the country.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever mistakes he may have made...I hope South Africa will
not forget the role he has played," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Democratic Party leader Tony Leon also expressed that outgoing
National Party leader De Klerk would and should be remembered for
the February 2, 1990 speech, in which he announced Mandela's
release and the unbanning of political organizations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
