<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Brunei Agree to Hold Regular Annual Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Brunei today
agreed to hold a regular meeting between the heads of the two
governments every year to discuss bilateral ties and cooperation
at the macro level.
</P>
<P>
This was the outcome of the bilateral meeting here today
between Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah of Brunei, who is also prime
minister, and Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, Malaysian
Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi told reporters after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders acknowledged the benefits of a regular meeting
and agreed that both countries take turns in hosting it and the
meeting next year will be held in Brunei's capital Bandar Sri
Begawan, Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
Although Malaysia and Brunei do not have any major bilateral
problems, the two leaders felt that regular meetings between
senior officials, ministers and heads of government of the two
countries would further boost understanding and relations, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"With this, it will be easier for us to deal with any matter
concerning bilateral ties between Malaysia and Brunei. If such a
spirit is not there... it will be more difficult," the foreign
BDH163WSD011S26PEQL17:0617:071671
minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Malaysia-Brunei Joint Commission will continue to
meet every year to discuss details and technical matters in
relation to the decisions reached at the meetings between their
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said Mahathir also informed the sultan of Malaysia's
stand on the speculative attacks on the currencies of Malaysia and
several other ASEAN members.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said he would express Malaysia's and several other
countries' firm stand on such "criminal acts" at the World
Bank-International Monetary Fund meetings in Hong Kong next month,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The prime ministers agreed to exchange information on similar
activities and to look for ways to jointly tackle the problem,
Abdullah said, adding Malaysia and Brunei also agreed on the need
for concerted efforts among the ASEAN nations to tackle the
problem.
</P>
<P>
The Brunei sultan arrived here Monday on a four-day state
visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
