<HEADLINE> South Korea Agrees on China's Entry Into WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 26 (Xinhua) -- South Korea agreed in talks with
China here today on the terms for China's entry into the World
Trade Organization (WTO), making it the first Asian country to
conclude such kind of talks.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Vice Minister of Chinese Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation Ministry Long Yongtu and South Korean Foreign
Ministry's Director General Lee Tae-shik signed the agreement
after two-day negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Trade and economic cooperation between China and South Korea
have marked a drastic rise since the two countries normalized
diplomatic ties in 1992, making China the third biggest trade
partner of South Korea and South Korea the fourth of this kind of
China.
</P>
<P>
Long Yongtu said the agreement would help promote development
of the bilateral trade and economic relations and also enhance the
bilateral cooperation in multi-national trade and economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government highly appreciates South Korea's
consistent support for China's entry into the WTO as well as its
flexible and realistic attitude during the negotiations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Lee Tae-shik said that South Korea would continue to support
China in the multi-national negotiations so as to help China win
the WTO membership as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
