<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- From 1932 to 1976, 62,000 Swedish citizens were sterilized
because of their assumed physical, mental, ``racial'' and other
defaults. The practice, which began in Sweden in 1922 when the
Institute of Racial Biology of Uppsala defined the first law on
racial purity, was legalized by the Social-Democrats who were in
power in Sweden since 1932 in order to ``improve the quality of
men.''
</P>
<P>
-- Leni Riefenstahl, the legendary woman movie shooter of the
Third Reich who is now 95 years old, had for the first time since
the end of the war her pictures displayed in a small exhibition in
Germany last week. The exhibition, which displayed about 40 cliches
from the film she shot at the 1936 Berlin Olympic Games and some
pictures she took in Sudan, had aroused a controversy in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Under the shadow of the controversy over the role Switzerland
played during World War II and Nazi Gold, the Swiss city Basle today
began to celebrate the 100th anniversary of the birth of Zionism in
the city, where Theodor Herzle, the founding father of modern
Zionism, declared that he founded the first Jewish state in Basle at
the first World Zionist Congress.
</P>
<P>
-- The American tobacco producers have agreed to pay 11.3 billion
U.S. dollars in 25 years to the government of Florida to compensate
for the health spending by the state for smoking linked diseases.
</P>
</TEXT>
