<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Improve Welfare of Ex-Combatants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe government
reinforced its commitment to improving the welfare of
ex-combatants.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance Herbert Murerwa said Monday that the
government would not hesitate to freeze other state activities to
raise funds for projects designed to assist former freedom
fighters, and for disability claims.
</P>
<P>
Murerwa said the government would honor its commitment to the
former freedom fighters and would bend over backwards to "ensure
that ex-combatants are well provided for".
</P>
<P>
He told the Chidyausiku Judicial Commission of Inquiry on
Ex-Combatants Fund that although the government was often cash
strapped, it would now place ex-combatants' needs on the same
priority list as education and health.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the government has made a commitment and will cut
other activities of the government to accommodate ex-combatants."
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of ex-combatants resorted recently to picketing
ruling Zanu (PF) party and government offices, including the
presidential residence, demanding disbursement of disability
pensions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
