<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labour Shortage Hits Zimbabwe's Tea Growers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The shortage of labour on tea
estates is growing in Zimbabwe despite efforts being made to
solve it through the introduction of machines, a local daily
paper, The Herald, reported today.
</P>
<P>
Eastern Highlands Plantations Limited, one of the country's
major tea and coffee producers said Monday the shortage of tea
plucking labour remained a major constraint to increased tea
production.
</P>
<P>
The paper reported tea and coffee estates and also cotton
growers were first hit by a labour shortage when hundreds of
Mozambicans who used to work on the farms were repatriated when
peace returned to their country.
</P>
<P>
Attempts to woo local labour has largely failed because of the
low wages offered by the farmers. Cotton growers have been quick
to introduce machines to pick the cotton but the quality of the
crop cannot match the hand-picked one which Zimbabwe has been
known to produce for decades.
</P>
<P>
This year, turnover for the tea and coffee producer rose by 56
percent due to improved quality of the tea and the better prices
on the market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
