<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Grow Grapes, Apples </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Uganda, an equatorial African
country, has decided to grow grapes and apples in the
southwestern Rwenzori Mountains, reported the local daily, The
New Vision today.
</P>
<P>
Rwenzori Mountains, 5590 meters above sea level, is the third
highest summit in africa.
</P>
<P>
South African investor Roland Hodoul was quoted as saying that
grapes and apples are grown in South Africa in areas with the
climatic conditions similar to that in the Rwenzori Mountains.
</P>
<P>
He said Uganda and South African investors will launch a
fruit-growing and processing project valued at three million U.S.
Dollars soon in Uganda's southwestern district of Kasese in
Rwenzori Mountain area.
</P>
<P>
The project will also include a processing plant to produce
10,000 tons of concentrate fruit juice annually.
</P>
<P>
He said the project would be a joint venture between South
African investors and the local population in Kasese through
non-governmental organization called Rwenzori Initiative (RI).
</P>
<P>
He said the by-product from the processing plant would be used
as animal feed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
