<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kabila Expects S. African Aid in Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Visiting President Laurent
Kabila of Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) are expecting
comprehensive help from South Africa to rebuild his country's
economy shattered in the civil war.
</P>
<P>
Local daily, The Citizen, today quoted Kabila as saying that
the most pressing need in his country was to establish roads and
links to the the interior to ensure that food grown there could
reach towns and cities.
</P>
<P>
"Our major problem is infrastructure...our most important
priority is roads, bridges and everything destroyed by the Mobutu
regime," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kabila took power of DRC, former Zaire, in May after his armed
forces, Alliance of Democratic Forces for the Liberation of
Congo-Zaire overwhelmed the then government troops led by Mobutu
Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
Referring to post-war reconstruction, Kabila also called on
South African President Nelson Mandela to expel former Zairean
generals and senior politicians who fled to South Africa after
the downfall of the Mobutu regime.
</P>
<P>
He accused them of using South Africa as a base to plot the
overthrow of the new-born DRC government, and suggest these people
have to go back home.
</P>
<P>
In response, Mandela said he had set up a team under Foreign
Minister Alfred Nzo to look into the allegations, noting his
government did not want its country to be a base for
destabilizing any country.
</P>
<P>
However, Mandela did not comment on the handover of the men
once loyal to ousted Mobutu.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
