<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Seeks Higher Taxes Against IMF Loan Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government intends
to introduce additional taxes and an anti-dumping duty in a move
to bridge the budget deficit gap widened by the International
Monetary Fund's key loan cut, local press reported today..
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Finance Minister Musalia Mudavadi is expected to submit
amendments to the Finance Bill to the parliament today to impose
additional taxes on motor vehicles, tobacco, beer, and other
goods, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Duty on all vehicles (excluding value-added tax) will rise
from the 10 percent proposed by the minister during the Budget in
June to 20 percent in a mini-Budget.
</P>
<P>
The prices of cigarettes, beer, wines, and spirits will
effectively go up once the parliament approves the changes
proposed in the Finance Bill due to be debated this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Mudavadi also intends to introduce anti-dumping or
countervailing duties on manufactured goods exported to Kenya
which either threaten local industry or may prevent its
establishment in the foreseeable future, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The targeted imported goods are expected to include secondhand
cars, beer, secondhand clothes, building materials and household
consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
The price of imported brands of cigarettes, cigars, snuff and
tobacco extracts is expected to go up considerably by a 25
percent duty rise.
</P>
<P>
All oils will get an additional five percent duty. Beer,
wines, spirits and sherries will go up by the same margin.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan Shilling strengthened against the U.S. Dollar to
about 60 Shillings a U.S. Dollar last Friday from previously
around 70, when the IMF decided to send a team to Kenya and the
Shilling made further gains Monday, opening at 64.74 against the
Dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
