<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Combining Onshore And Offshore Oil Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 26 (Xinhua) -- China will spend 600 million
U.S. dollars combining onshore exploration with offshore oil
exploration at the Suizhong 36-1 oilfield in the Bohai Sea.
</P>
<P>
The new exploration technique is suited to Suizhong 36-1, the
biggest offshore oilfield in China, and will help reduce
production costs.
</P>
<P>
China National Offshore Oil Company's Bohai Company, which is
responsible for oil exploration in Bohai Bay, signed a contract on
August 14 with Liaoning province's Suizhong County government for
rights to use 970 mu (one mu equals to 0.0667 ha) of county land
and 1,170 m of coastline.
</P>
<P>
According to a Bohai Oil Company official, the company will
build a multi-purpose base for production and living with
facilities for oil and gas processing, storage, and marketing, and
a new oil berth.
</P>
<P>
Suizhong 36-1 was discovered in 1988 in Liaodong Bay, 70 km
from Suizhong Port. It covers 48 sq.km. and has proven reserves of
289 million tons of oil. It has produced two million tons of oil
and gas a year since the Bohai Oil Company began trial offshore
development in 1988 at a cost of 1.8 billion yuan, on a
6.55-sq. km. area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
