<HEADLINE> Russia to Take Tougher Action on Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said today his government would take tougher actions to fight
against crimes in the country, the Presidential Information Office
said.
</P>
<P>
When meeting with Prosecutor-General Yurin Skuratov, Yeltsin
said the rate of crime is still high in Russia although the rate
of crime in the first seven months of this year dropped six
percent over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
He said that law enforcement bodies should spare no effort to
combat the economic crime, which is increasing in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Although the set-up of a special force to fight against
economic crime has been delayed, he said, the government has the
ability to combat crimes so as to let the people live a more
stable life.
</P>
<P>
Skuratov submitted to Yeltsin a report on the basic policies
for combatting crimes, which is aimed at proposing ways to
mobilize all forces of society to fight against crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
