<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Encourages Public-Interest Advertisements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 26 (Xinhua) -- New regulations on
advertisements in the public interests have been promulgated by
China's central government on the amount of time and space.
</P>
<P>
The regulations are contained in a circular issued jointly by
the Propaganda Department of the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China, the State Administration for Industry
and Commerce, the Ministry of Radio, Film and Television, and the
Press and Publication Administration.
</P>
<P>
The regulations state that the time radio or television
programs devotes to public interest ads must not be less than a
third of the time used for commercial messages.
</P>
<P>
The space given by newspapers and magazines to public interest
ads also must be no less than a third of that given to commercial
messages.
</P>
<P>
Billboards also have to devote a certain amount of space to
public service ads, and the specifics on this are still to be
worked out.
</P>
<P>
According to the circular, public-interest ads of any
enterprise can carry the name of the enterprise in a specific
amount of time and space, but not the name of products, the
trademark, or services of the enterprise. Commercials in the form
of public-interest ads are strictly prohibited. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
