<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Chess Champion Karpov Arrives in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 26 (Xinhua) -- World chess champion Anatoly
Karpov of Russia arrived in Beijing Tuesday for a seven-day visit
and exhibition matches.
</P>
<P>
The 46-year-old grandmaster, who won titles at the 1975, 1978,
1981, 1993 and 1996 world chess championships, was warmly welcomed
at the Beijing Capital Airport by the officials of the Chinese
Chess Association.
</P>
<P>
Karpov will play three simultaneous exhibition matches against
Chinese players during his stay. He will face six top women
players on August 27, then 16 youngsters on August 30. The last
exhibition match, one versus six juniors, will be played on
September 1.
</P>
<P>
All the exhibition matches will be televised and former world
women's champion Xie Jun of China will be one of the commentators
during the matches.
</P>
<P>
The Russian grandmaster said after his arrival that the Chinese
women players had made a great progress in recent years.
</P>
<P>
He said:" They are expected to achieve better results in the
future while the Chinese male players need to work hard to catch
up the world level."
</P>
<P>
Chen Zude, President of the Chinese Chess Association, said
Chinese players will take the opportunity to learn from the world
champion who visited China for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Also arriving in Beijing together with Karpov were his wife and
and his party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
