<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Stone Age Relics Discovered in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
dup up more than 160 pieces of relices from the Neolithic Age
(about 10,000 to 4,000 years ago) in a village in Baoding City in
north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists say they believe that the finds in Nanzhuangtou
village are the earliest new stone age evidence in China.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists from Beijing University, Hebei University and
local archeology departments have unearthed a large number of
relics in the village that include animal and bird bones,
charcoal, plant seeds, pottery shards, and stone implements.
</P>
<P>
Experts here said the discovery of a millstone and pollen
indicate that rudimantary agriculture appeared about 10,000 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
They said that the new items and the pottery shards show that
the history of pottery in China goes back 2,000 years more than
present records indicate.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists say that the Nanzhuangtou finds are important for
research on the geology, climate, and ecological conditions of
that time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
