<HEADLINE> Desert Tourist Spots Hot in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Zhongwei county in the Ningxia
Hui Autonomous Region of northwest China plans to set up a
Shapotou Tourist Zone in a desert area and along the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
The zone is expected to cover 140,000 sq km and to give
tourists an opportunity to hear the unique "sand-sound" of the
deserts, and a chance to try their hand at camel-riding,
desert-cruising, and river-rafting.
</P>
<P>
The project will cost over 40 million yuan and is scheduled to
take shape by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Shapotou became the country's first national nature reserve
with a desert ecology, in 1984, and was one of 500 places in the
world praised by the United Nations for progress in environmental
protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
