<HEADLINE> Ugandans Still Depend on Traditional Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- About 85 percent of Uganda's
population still depend on traditional medicine and practices,
reported the local daily, The New Vision, today.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni was quoted as saying that,
"it is not, therefore, a matter of rejection but of
unaffordability (for modern medicine) that sustains the dominance
of traditional medicine."
</P>
<P>
He made the remark in an address at the opening ceremony of a
ten-day international conference on human rights and medicine
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Museveni advised medical students to address the clash of
rights in practicing medicine because sometimes cultural and
religious practices work against the proper practice of medicine
and the maintenance of health.
</P>
<P>
He said, "in some of our communities sexual courtesies is an
aspect of hospitality, in others wives are inherited and many
more."
</P>
<P>
He also called for the protection of patients from the greed
and mercilessness of quacks and unethical medical practitioners.
</P>
