<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Calls For Mutually Beneficial Cooperation With ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said
today the cooperation between China and ASEAN countries should be
oriented toward the 21st century on the basis of mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
In a speech entitled "Strengthen Mutually Beneficial
Cooperation and Promote Common Prosperity", delivered to a group
of Singapore businessmen on the last day of his three-day visit,
Li said China and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) countries need to expand areas of cooperation in order for
their respective strength to complement each other.
</P>
<P>
He said the economies of China and ASEAN countries, having
their respective features and advantages, are highly complementary
to each other.
</P>
<P>
He said the two sides should, proceeding from their own actual
conditions, maximize their respective favorable factors and
minimize the unfavorable so as to complement each other with their
advantages and conduct mutually beneficial cooperation based on
equality with a view to seeking common development.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China and ASEAN countries also need to strengthen
coordination and cooperation in the financial field.
</P>
<P>
He said compared with the developed countries, "the economic
strength of countries and regions like ours" is still relatively
weak and the financial system is inadequate, which bears certain
financial risks and is susceptible to the impact of the turbulence
of the international financial market in the course of its
development.
</P>
<P>
He said China and ASEAN countries should increase their
coordination and cooperation in finance and step up exchanges of
information to keep each other informed so as to ward off
international financial speculation.
</P>
<P>
He added both sides should draw lessons from previous financial
crises in the world, keeping a high degree of vigilance,
strengthening financial regulation and improving the financial
system so as to forestall and reduce financial risks to the
minimum and ensure a sound growth of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China and ASEAN countries should take firm hold of
the converging point where they share extensive common interests
and lift the mutually beneficial cooperation onto a new high.
</P>
<P>
He said the mutually beneficial cooperation between China and
ASEAN countries is a long-term strategy with the future in mind
rather than an expediency.
</P>
<P>
He said the cooperation between the two sides, focused on the
whole world instead of merely the region, conduces not only to
their respective economic development, but also to peace and
stability of the Asia-Pacific region and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
He added that the mutually beneficial cooperation between China
and ASEAN countries, also serving as the foundation for political
diversity in the world, can be predicted to be more dynamic and
vibrant in the days ahead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thailand Stands Firm on U.S. Pressure for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is sticking firmly to
its own offers to financial liberalization under its commitment to
the World Trade Organization (WTO), as the United States presses
further on the matter before the WTO opens the next round of talks
on financial services in September.
</P>
<P>
Chaiyawat Wibulswasdi, governor of the Bank of Thailand, said
Monday that Thailand has opened its financial market sufficiently
and it will stand firm with its original offers.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has issued new bank licenses to foreign
banks recently and it also has allowed foreign banks to install
automatic teller machines (ATMs) and expand their branches in the
country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand also has moved to relax its rules on the ceiling limit
for foreign holdings in local banks and finance firms and Thailand
will continue to do so on a case-by-case basis, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The governor reiterated that Thailand will not change its
offers it set originally.
</P>
<P>
Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Jeffrey Lang made a trip to
Japan, South Korea, the Philippines, Malaysia, Indonesia, India
and Thailand to lobby before the WTO is scheduled to conclude a
global agreement on financial services liberalization on December
12 this year.
</P>
<P>
At the end of his visit to Thailand Monday, the U.S. envoy
urged Thailand to improve its financial liberalization offers to
the WTO as a measure to restore investors' confidence in the Thai
economy.
</P>
<P>
The WTO talks present a further opportunity for Thailand to do
so, Lang said.
</P>
<P>
On the International Monetary Fund (IMF) standby arrangement
for Thailand, Lang said that the U.S. welcomes the IMF step to
support Thailand's stabilization program as a significant step
towards the restoration of financial stability.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that the U.S. is worrying that the
current currency turmoil in Southeast Asia might make some WTO
members block the efforts to open up the financial services
market.
</P>
<P>
Lang said that the U.S. will be flexible in working creatively
and constructively with countries to conclude a WTO financial
services agreement that can help address structural weakness and
reinforce market confidence where needed.
</P>
<P>
In response, Thai Commerce Minister Narongchai Akrasanee said
that the U.S. should adjust its role from an aggressor in
pressuring for the financial liberalization to a supporter to
assist smaller countries in maximizing the use of foreign capital,
as the country is believed to cause the current chaos in the world
financial market.
</P>
<P>
The WTO should draw a lesson from the current turmoil in
Southeast Asia as overexposure to foreign capital may lead to
disaster on financial markets in any country, he said.
</P>
<P>
The WTO should assist members in improving their debt market
accounting and appraisal standards, otherwise exposure to foreign
capital through financial liberalization might cause problems for
some WTO members, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister attributed the current financial turmoil in
Thailand to an inadequate supervisory system, lack of a deep
foreign exchange market, heavy short-term debts and a substandard
assets evaluation system in the country.
</P>
<P>
He urged the U.S. to use its expertise to help developing
countries prepare mechanisms to avoid a possible disaster from
overexposure to foreign capital inflow and outflow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Industrial Base Attracts More Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning province, one of
China's traditional heavy industrial bases, utilized 1.2 billion
US dollars in foreign investment in the first half of this year,
up 74 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The figure is 18 percentage points higher than the country's
average.
</P>
<P>
Investment from Liaoning's 15,535 foreign-funded enterprises
recorded 984 million US dollars in the period, up 69.7 percent
from last year's corresponding period.
</P>
<P>
Gao Guozhu, vice-govoner of the province, told Xinhua that
Liaoning is home to one tenth of China's large-and medium-sized
enterprises and has 300-billion-yuan in fixed assets, which is
appealing to investors to increase their investment in the
province.
</P>
<P>
In the first half, foreign investors added 320 million US
dollars to their initial investment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, two enterprise groups in Dalian, a port city in the
province, has attracted 172 million US dollars by issuing B shares
in the six months, and the Anshan Iron and Steel Company, a
leading steel production center in China, will issue H shares this
year.
</P>
<P>
The province has newly approved 760 solely foreing-funded
projects, 52 projects of which involve 20 million US dollars each,
with their combined contracted investment hitting 1.1 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some 350 million US dollars were utilized in infrastructure
projects, 17 percent of the total contracted investment.
</P>
<P>
In the first half year, Liaoning used 390 million US dollars to
accelerate the reform of its state large-and medium-sized
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Over 50 big foreign companies and financial groups like Japan's
Mitsubishi and the US General Motors Corporation have invested in
the province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
