<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Revenue Collection Trails Behind Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The latest estimates show that
the revenue collection of Pakistan is trailing behind the
specified target, a local newspaper report said today.
</P>
<P>
The revenue collection during July, the first month of the
1997-98 fiscal year, was about 15.9 billion rupees (398 million
U.S. dollars) and the projected estimates for August showed just a
little improvement over the previous month, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The tax revenue target for the first quarter of the fiscal
year, July to September, is 65 billion rupees (1.63 billion
dollars) or 20 percent of the yearly target of 324 billion rupees
(8.1 billion dollars), according to the report.
</P>
<P>
That means July's revenue collection is 5.7 billion rupees (143
million dollars) short of the target.
</P>
<P>
As the revenue collection trends of August are not very
encouraging, said the report, there is every possibility that the
government may miss the quarterly revenue collection targets.
</P>
<P>
"On paper, the government has done everything fine, policies
are good and the intention is right, but implementation is not up
to the mark," the report quoted a senior economist as saying.
</P>
<P>
"After substantially reducing tax and tariff rates, the
government needs to squeeze out the due taxes from all the
sectors," the economist said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
