<HEADLINE> Sampras, Seles Win First Round without Difficulty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Both men's and women's stars
Pete Sampras and Monic Seles got through their first round easily
with a stragight-set win recpectively in the U.S. Open tennis
championships Monday night.
</P>
<P>
American defending champion Sampras used only 94 minutes to
trounce Australian qualifier Todd Larkham 6-3, 6-1, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
"The first match of a slam is always one you just want to get
through," said the four-time titlist, who started to his 10th
U.S. Open campaign.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, fourth seed Goran Ivanisevic of Croatia went out in
the first round for the third time in four years as the
semifinalist last year shocked 4-6, 7-5, 6-1, 7-6 by 91st-ranked
Romanian Dinu Pescariu.
</P>
<P>
"You cannot win matches when you play like that," said the
dejected Croat, who sprayed a whopping 75 unforced errors and
landed just 48 percent of his first serves in play.
</P>
<P>
In a somewhat lesser surprise, Todd Martin picked off his
countryman and world former number one Jim Courier of the United
States 3-6, 6-3, 6-4, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Martin was making his return after a six-month absence
following elbow surgery.
</P>
<P>
Women's second seed and twice-champion Seles, who played the
first-ever match under the lights at the splendid new Arthur Ashe
Stadium, made just three unforced errors in the 22-minute first
set on her way to a 6-1, 6-2 thumping of Kristie Boogert of the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
"It was nice to have a pretty fast match out there," said
Seles, who is recovering from high fever and a throat virus that
forced her to pull out in the middle of the Atlanta tournament
last week.
</P>
<P>
Seles, runner-up to injured five-time champion Steffi Graf the
past two years, won back-to-back tournaments prior to pulling out
last week in Atlanta. But she was not ready to pronounce herself a
favorite for the 1997 title. 
</P>
</TEXT>
