<HEADLINE> Beijing Hosts More Tourists From Southeast Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Beijing recorded robust growth
in the number of tourists arriving from Southeast Asia during the
first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
Some 60,000 tourists from Malaysia visited Beijing in the first
half year, up 27.45 percent on the same 1996 period. The figure
far surpassed the number of tourists from the Republic of Korea,
Beijing's third largest tourist source.
</P>
<P>
Some 18,400 Thai tourists visited the city, up 11.58 percent,
with further increases recorded for tourists from India, the
Philippines and Mongolia,
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists from the United States, the city's
second largest tourist source, continued to grow, with 96,800 US
tourists visiting the city during the first six months of the
year, representing an increase of 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists from Japan, Beijing's largest tourist
source, declined, with 173,500 Japanese tourists visiting the city
in the first half of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
