<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysians Urged to Increase Savings to Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian State Bank
Governor Ahmad Mohd Don today urged Malaysians to increase the
level of national savings to help stabilize the currency market
which is now affected by currency speculators' manipulation.
</P>
<P>
Although a lot of attention is being given to the movements of
the currency market which is not so stable right now, Malaysians
should work towards building the foundations towards greater
economic success for the nation and one of these would be a high
level of savings, he said at the opening of a seminar on
encouraging savings here.
</P>
<P>
With a high level of savings, he said, the country would be
able to achieve a high level of investment, and this development
would enable Malaysia to raise its productivity without having to
depend on foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
"If we are too dependent on foreign funds, we will face higher
risks and higher cost of funds, especially in a not very stable
market as is happening now," the governor said, adding that in
view of this, Malaysians need to raise their level of savings to
lessen those risks.
</P>
<P>
The foreign exchange market has become less stable following
speculative attacks by speculators which had caused Malaysian
ringgit (local currency) to fall.
</P>
<P>
The central bank chief said that in order to reduce the risks
from the instability of the currency market, savings in the
country ought to be expanded although Malaysia has one of the
highest savings rates in the world, which was 37.8 percent of the
gross national product last year.
</P>
<P>
"Although Malaysia had maintained the high savings rate over
the past three decades with an average of 28.6 percent between
1970 and 1996, we should not be satisfied with this achievement,"
Ahmad said.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia still depended a lot on foreign funds for
investments, especially in the manufacturing sector which was
supposed to spearhead the nation's march towards developed nation
status under Vision 2020.
</P>
<P>
"The increased competition in attracting foreign investors as
well as the currency movements have revealed the necessity to
raise the level of savings so that economic growth is not
adversely affected in the future," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
