<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Ends Singaporean Tour, Leaves for Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng left
here today for home by special plane after wounding up his
three-day official visit to Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier arrived in Singapore, the last leg of his
two-nation Southeast Asian tour, on Sunday as guest of Singaporean
Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong. Li visited Malaysia on August 21-24.
</P>
<P>
Seeing Li off at the airport were Singaporean Minister for Home
Affairs Wong Kan Seng, Chinese Ambassador to Singapore Chen Baoliu
and others.
</P>
<P>
Aboard the same plane for home are Li's wife Zhu Lin and his
entourage who were accompanying him on the three-day visit to
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
During his visit here, Li met with President Ong Teng Cheong,
Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong and Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew and
had in-depth exchanges of views with them on promoting the
Sino-Singapore relations, and on international and regional issues
of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Li also witnessed the signing of a memorandum of understanding
for expanding air services between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The local press widely held that the first visit to Singapore
by the Chinese head of government since the two countries set up
diplomatic ties seven years ago would serve to push the bilateral
friendly relations of cooperation up to a new high.
</P>
<P>
Li's last visit to Singapore was in August 1990.  
</P>
