<HEADLINE> India's Cement Consumption Grows 8 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Despite a slowdown in
industrial activity in the financial year 1996-97, cement
consumption grew at a compounded annual growth rate of 8 percent
and is expected to grow 9 percent till the financial year-2000,
said a research report by the State Bank of India on capital
markets here today.
</P>
<P>
The country's cement export this year grew to 1.68 million
tons, an increase of 11 percent. The first quarter of this year
witnessed a 17 percent rise in exports as against 6 percent in the
corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total exports, 37 percent went to Nepal. The other major
importers were Bangladesh and Sri Lanka, the report said.
</P>
<P>
A spurt in infrastructure spending and industrial activity in
the country could lead to a further increase in cement demand, the
report added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
