<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mountain Slopes in Guizhou Become Fertile Farmland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, August 26 (Xinhua) -- More than 260,000 hectares of
mountainside have been transformed into terraced fields in
southwest China's Guizhou province in the past six years, using a
total investment of 140 million yuan (17 million US dollars)
provided by local farmers in 30 counties, in addition to
government allocations.
</P>
<P>
To facilitate farming, farmers have built mountain roads with
the total length reaching 947,000 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
As a result, during the past six years, the province's total
acreae of cultivated fields has increased by 33,000 ha.
</P>
<P>
Terracing sloped fields has raised the region's ability to
combat drought and brought in increased grain output. Corn output
per ha has gone up from 1,500 kg to 5,250 kg, and paddy rice from
3,000 kg to 6,750 kg.
</P>
<P>
Local farmers get 100 million yuan (12 million US dollars)
every year by planting economic crops in the terraced fields, such
as peanuts, chili peppers and watermelon.
</P>
<P>
Terracing in karst mountain areas is a successful way to end
poverty, improve farm conditions, increase grain output and
farmers' income, said Wu Yixia, governor of Guizhou province.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent decision by the province, 67,000 ha more
mountain slopes will be transformed into terraced fields annually
from now on. The provincial government is to provide 20 million
yuan (2.4 million US dollars) every year for the construction of
water conservation facilities.
</P>
<P>
The province is expected to build up 540,000 ha of farmland by
the year of 2000, Wu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
