<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thailand Stands Firm on U.S. Pressure for Finance Liberalization by Xiong Ping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is sticking firmly to
its own offers to financial liberalization under its commitment to
the World Trade Organization (WTO), as the United States presses
further on the matter before the WTO is to open the next round of
talks on financial services in September.
</P>
<P>
Chaiyawat Wibulswasdi, governor of the Bank of Thailand, said
Monday that Thailand has opened its financial market sufficiently
and it will stand firm with its original offers and not offer
more.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has issued new bank licenses to foreign
banks recently and it also has allowed foreign banks to install
automatic teller machines (ATMs) and expand their branches in the
country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand also has moved to relax its rules on the ceiling limit
for foreign holdings in local banks and finance firms and Thailand
will continue to do so on a case-by-case basis, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The governor reiterated that Thailand will not change its
offers it set originally.
</P>
<P>
Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Jeffrey Lang made a trip to
Japan, South Korea, the Philippines, Malaysia, Indonesia, India
and Thailand to lobby before the WTO is scheduled to conclude a
global agreement on financial services liberalization on December
12 this year.
</P>
<P>
At the end of his visit to Thailand Monday, the U.S. envoy
urged Thailand to improve its financial liberalization offers to
the WTO as a measure to restore investors' confidence in the Thai
economy.
</P>
<P>
The WTO talks present a further opportunity for Thailand to do
so, Lang said.
</P>
<P>
On the International Monetary Fund (IMF) standby arrangement
for Thailand, Lang said that the U.S. welcomes the IMF step to
support Thailand's stabilization program as a significant step
towards the restoration of financial stability.
</P>
<P>
