<HEADLINE> India's Foreign Investment Approvals Shoot Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 26 (Xinhua) -- There has been an unusual
surge in foreign direct investment (FDI) approvals in India in the
first five months of this year, the Economic Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the FDI approvals reached a record high of
7.45 billion U.S. dollars against a total of 10.34 billion
approved in 1996, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"Going at this rate, it should exceed the figure of 15 billion
U.S. dollars before the end of 1997," the newspaper quoted
government sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The total approvals of FDI in both 1995 and 1996 were about 10
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The actual inflow in U.S. dollar terms in the first five months
of this year has been about 1.71 billion against the total inflow
of 2.4 billion in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Investment Promotion Board (FIPB) predicts an
actual inflow of four billion dollars this year, almost twice the
last year figure. The total inflow since 1991 is estimated to be
8.09 billion dollars while the total FDI approvals between 1991 to
1997 (up to May) is pegged at 37.12 billion dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
