<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 06:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car Thefts in Israel on Sharp Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Car thefts in Israel have been
continuning to rise sharply as some 21,500 cars were stolen in the
first half of the year, 30 percent up from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Zeev Weiner, President of Israel Association of Insurance
Agents, was quoted by Israeli news agency Itim as saying Monday
that the number of stolen vehicles in Israel would be 45,000 at
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
In July alone, more than 4,000 vehicles were stolen in Israel,
or 28 percent more than in the same month last year, Weiner said.
</P>
<P>
Weiner attributed the drop in insurance companies' profits to
the rise in the number of stolen vehicles over the past year, and
he blamed the government for not allocating sufficient resources
to combat the problem.
</P>
<P>
Weiner called on the government to crack down on car thefts,
adding that his association was considering a petition to the
High Court against the government for "not doing enough to
protect its citizens and their property."
</P>
<P>
It is believed there is a well-organized net for car thefts
which links Israel and the Palestinian self-rule areas. Most of
the stolen cars ended up in the Palestinian areas, where they were
disassembled into parts, either to be re-assembled to build new
cars or to be sold to customers at low prices.
</P>
<P>
"One has to act as in a war," Weiner said. "The theft of cars
is first and foremost a personal threat to all citizens of the
state, more than a financial loss."
</P>
<P>
Israeli insurance companies are scheduled to hold a conference
on September 8 in Eilat to discuss, among other things, the threat
of car thefts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
