<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increasing Use of Biological Potash Fertilizer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAODING, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Environmental-friendly
biological potash fertilizer has been used on more than 30 kinds
of plants in China and more than four million ha of farmland,
according to a recent seminar.
</P>
<P>
The fertilizer was developed by the Hebei Academy of
Sciences. It dissolves compounds in the soil into potash by
biological means, after which potash elements can be absorbed by
plants.
</P>
<P>
The fertilizer can greatly increase crop output and improve
soil quality. It also does not harm humans.
</P>
<P>
Sixty percent of China's farmland lacks potash and resources
are scarce, and potash deposits are only found in northwest
China's Qinghai province.
</P>
<P>
To increase the use of the fertilizer, a production line with
an annual capacity of 10,000 tons began test operation in Baoding
in April. It is listed as one of the country's key projects and is
the largest in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Hebei Academy of Sciences has held two training sessions on
the new fertilizer for 44 foreign students from 13 countries.
</P>
<P>
The fertilizer has also been exported to India, Thailand, and
Vietnam. Joint ventures are expected to be set up in India and
Thailand to produce the fertilizer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sri Lanka's 100-Day Military Offensive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 26 (Xinhua) -- On May 13, Sri Lanka's
government troops launched a major military offensive against the
Tamil rebels to recapture 75 kilometers of the main South-North
highway through territory held by the rebels of the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE).
</P>
<P>
The operation code-named "Jaya Sikuru" (Certain Victory)
launched by 25,000 troops has after 100 days of battle enabled the
forces to recapture a mere 25 kilometers of roadway at a cost of
500 soldiers dead and 3,000 others injured together with six main
battle tanks and a Russian-built amphibious armored personnel
carrier worth 90,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to military statistics, the loss of the LTTE is
reported to be over 2,000 dead but the rebels deny this.
</P>
<P>
Since last Tuesday, a fierce battle was launched to recapture
the strategic town of Puliyankulam standing at the cross roads to
the entrance of the Northern province.
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports, at a cost of 95 soldiers dead
and over 300 injured, the forces recaptured the Puliyankulam
railway station three kilometers away from the town proper Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Heavily fortified LTTE bunkers are offering severe resistance
to the forces who are trying hard to inch their way forward, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the current operation was the re-opening of
the Vavuniya-Jaffna highway known as A 9 number road. This was to
re-establish a government controlled land route between Vavuniya
and the Jaffna Peninsula through the Northern mainland controlled
to a great extent by the LTTE.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the road would help the government transport
essential food items and construction materials in great volume at
cheap cost to the Jaffna Peninsula. It would also help the armed
forces maintain a main supply route to military positions over
land.
</P>
<P>
Currently transportation is only by sea and air at heavy cost.
</P>
<P>
However, from the rebels' point of view, the loss of
Puliyankulam town will bring the army perilously close to the
Mankulam-Mullaitivu road which splits their territory stretching
from the West coast to the East coast where most of the rebel
camps are concentrated.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, Mullaitivu is the largest town in the rebel
territory and they would not want the military anywhere there.
Hence one of the fiercest battles can be expected during the
forces effort to recapture Puliyankulam town.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the slow progress of the Jaya Sikuru troops, there
has been increasing vulnerablitity to rebel counter-attacks. The
LTTE rebels have launched three major counter-offensives during
the 100 days of fighting and both sides suffered heavy losses.
</P>
<P>
They even almost downed an aircraft with a Stinger missile.
</P>
<P>
The troops appear to have been caught in a vicious circle. As
troop positions get dispersed vulnerability increases and the
rebels exploit it, some Tamil sources pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The lack of adequate manpower to hold and fortify captured
areas is an additional problem faced by the government forces,
they added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Tightens Rules for Finance Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 26 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand has
introduced new rules concerning the non-performing loans of banks
and finance firms in a bid to strengthen its supervision over the
country's financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rules, commercial banks and finance companies,
from January 1 next year, must count loans on which borrowers have
not paid interest for over six months as non-performing loans,
regardless of whether they are fully or partly collateralized.
</P>
<P>
This measure will better reflect the loan problems in the
country's financial system and force financial institutions to act
early to prevent the problems from aggravating, officials from the
central bank said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, fully collateralized loans are considered
non-performing in Thailand when the borrowers failed to pay
interest for 12 months.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said the new rules will certainly make the
non-performing loans, which are now estimated at 11 to 12 percent
of the total loans in Thailand, further rise.
</P>
<P>
Commercial banks will have to raise lending rates to offset the
higher non-performing loans, they added.
</P>
<P>
High non-performing loans are already expected by foreign
investors, so higher figures may not surprise them, according to
Thirachai Phuvanatnaranubala, director of the central bank's
Financial Institutions Supervision Department.
</P>
<P>
Thirachai also said that the central bank would tighten the
credit approval criteria of banks and finance firms through a
tougher check and broader appraisal system, including involving
more supervisors or institutions into the approval procedures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Opposition Drums up Protest Against Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's major opposition
parties are expected to announce their "tougher" anti-government
agitation programs at their separate public rallies today, in a
bid to drum up support for a movement against the fuel price hike.
</P>
<P>
Following a dawn-to-dusk general strike Sunday, the largest
opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) today held a new
round of country-wide demonstrations to keep their protest alive.
</P>
<P>
Some small opposition parties, including Jamaat-e-Islami and
the dissident faction of Jatiya (national) Party, are also
expected to hold their rallies this afternoon, said informed
sources.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the opposition parties in a joint
meeting Monday chalked out "tougher" programs, which include
processions towards the Parliament building simultaneously on
August 30, the day the sixth session of the Parliament is
scheduled to begin.
</P>
<P>
The parties also planned to submit separate memorandums to the
Speaker, complaining against what they call the government's
tendency to take major policy decisions bypassing the Parliament.
They would also seek the Speaker's intervention in such cases.
</P>
<P>
The government on August 18 refixed the prices of all petroleum
products, which triggered sharp reactions among different
political parties and transport circles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
