<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brunei Continues Employing Nepali Gurkhas: Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Brunei officials have denied
that their country has stopped recruiting former British Gurkha
Army officers into its security unit, Nepali newspapers reported
today.
</P>
<P>
They have also denied that there was an immediate plan to stop
the recruitment of the renowned Nepalese fighters, the Nepali
newspapers quoted a Brunei newspaper report as saying.
</P>
<P>
But there is a long-term plan to eventually phase them out of
the Gurkha Reserve Unit (GRU) in Brunei, where some 2,000 Nepalese
are working, the officials added.
</P>
<P>
They said members of the GRU are the ex-army personnel of the
British forces who have been directly hired by the Brunei
government as security guards and not as soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Nepali newspapers reported early this month that the government
of Brunei had decided to stop recruiting former British Gurkha
Army officers into the GRU and that all the Nepali officers
working in the GRU had been disarmed for acting against army
disciplines.
</P>
<P>
The reports also said some Gurkhas formed a group within the
GRU and raised money in the name of fighting a case against the
British government for equal pension as being enjoyed by their
British counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The Brunei officials have confirmed the disarming of the GRU,
but said this was done long before the crisis in the GRU.
</P>
<P>
The unnamed Brunei newspaper said the recent crisis in the GRU
was actually one between some Gurkha ex-servicemen and their
former British commanders.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed in 1947 between Britain, India and
Nepal, British and Indian armies can recruit Nepalese, who are
called Gurkha soldiers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
