<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Cultural Heritage Valued low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Italy's cultural heritage, usually
described as "priceless," has in fact had a price-tag pinned on it
by state accountants, amazingly, just one twelfth of the value of
the country's defense weaponry.
</P>
<P>
The figure emerged from the latest estimate of state assets,
but the state accountants wryly admitted that it is "clearly
undervalued."
</P>
<P>
According to estimates based on the 1995 budget, Italian
heritage assets are worth about 3.9 trillion lire (2.3 billion
U.S. dollars), the accountants said. That compares to more than 49
trillion lire (28 billion dollars) for all the weapons owned by
Italy's armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Another surprising fact was that about two thirds of the
heritage value comes from library collections: 2.6 trillion
lire. Only 1.3 trillion is put down as the value of assets owned
by the Cultural Heritage Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The accountants said all the monuments and art works are valued
low because the 1927 law sets no guidelines for reassessing the
initial book value.
</P>
<P>
Heritage assets were valued even lower in the past, the
accountants said. Through most of the 1990s they were put at
around 2 trillion lire, rising to 2.4 trillion in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Half of U.S. Capital's Young Blacks Involved in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Half the young black men in
the District of Columbia, the capital of the United States, are
under criminal justice supervision on any given day, the National
Center on Institutions and Alternatives reported today.
</P>
<P>
The group, in a study focused on black men aged 18 to 35, found
that half the young black people are in prison, on probation or
parole, or out on bond or a warrant.
</P>
<P>
The report said by the time a young black man reaches the age
of 35, his chance of having spent time locked up exceeds 80
percent.
</P>
<P>
District Mayor Marion Barry called the findings "alarming and
disappointing."
</P>
<P>
A nationwide study in 1995 estimated that one in three black
men was involved in the criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the high rates to the use of law
enforcement to manage social problems, including mental illness
and drug abuse, which were previously handled by other means.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
