<HEADLINE> Ukraine, U.S. Hold Joint Naval Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine and the United States
started their joint naval exercise in Crimea today despite protest
from some members in parliament.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, code-named Sea Breeze-97, is a seven-stage mock
relief operation which aims to provide and escort humanitarian aid
to an imaginary Orange Republic after a major earthquake.
</P>
<P>
The marine stage of the exercise is supposed to be carried out
in Crimea's offing followed by a landing operation at the Broad
Lawn training range in the Mykolaiv region.
</P>
<P>
About 25 warships and supportive vessels and some planes from
Ukraine, the United States, Bulgaria, Turkey, Romania and Georgia
are taking part in the week-long maneuver.
</P>
<P>
Only 300 marines from Ukraine and the U.S. will participate in
the land exercise, which is to be held near Odessa. Greece, Italy,
India, Canada, Britain, Lithuania, Moldova are posed as
observers.
</P>
<P>
However, Sea Breeze-97 has met a running fire from some
deputies in the Ukrainian parliament. Residents in Crimean, who
are mostly Russians, are holding protest rallies against the
exercise.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, about 50 pro-Russian protesters showed up in
Donuzlav, which is a Ukrainian naval base and where the marine
exercise will be staged. Protesters chanted anti-U.S. slogans and
poured severe criticism over the Ukrainian authorities.
</P>
<P>
On August 23, some anti-NATO protesters picketed the House of
Navel Officers in Donuzlav when a press conference was going on.
</P>
<P>
The land exercise which had been planned near Sevastopol, the
main base of the Russian Black Sea Fleet, had been forced to move
to Odessa due to intense pressure from both local residents and
the Ukrainian parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
