<HEADLINE> Child-Abduction by Parents Increases in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Rome, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The number of children being
snatched by one of their parents is increasing in Italy,
according to data released by the European central bureau for
justice for minors.
</P>
<P>
One cause seems to be the growing number of marriages between
Italian and foreigners. In the case of a separation, difficulties
over child custody rights frequently lead to the child being
abducted by the foreign partner and brought up abroad.
</P>
<P>
Between 1995 and the first month of 1997, there were 159 cases
of "international" child-snatching in Italy. Despite international
laws and conventions, these cases prove particularly hard to
resolve. In 1995, solutions were found for only 42 of the 69 cases
reported. The figures for 1996 were 54 out of 78. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0237 </DOCNO>
