<HEADLINE> Krajisnik Boycotts Bosnian Presidential Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Momcilo Krajisnik, the Serb
member of the Bosnian Presidency, refused to attend a presidential
session Monday, citing reasons related to the political crisis in
the Republic of Srpska.
</P>
<P>
Krajisnik did not show up at the scheduled meeting of the
presidency but sent a letter to his colleagues saying that he is
temporarily prevented from taking part in its work, said Mirza
Hajric, an advisor to Alija Izetbegovic, Muslim member and
chairman of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Westendorp, the international community's High
Representative in Bosnia, later told reporters that Krajisnik has
said that he will not participate in the work of the common
Bosnian institutions until the problem of the Banja Luka stations
is solved.
</P>
<P>
Krajisnik's boycott came amid intensified power struggle
between him and the President of the Republic of Srpska, Biljana
Plavsic, whose supporters have taken over police stations in Banja
Luka with the help of the NATO-led Stablization Force (SFOR).
</P>
<P>
Monday's session was due to discuss a compromise proposed by
Westendorp on the issue of draft laws on citizenship and
passports, which has been accepted in principle by the Muslim and
Croat sides but still resisted by the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
Westendorp said that owing to the present circumstances he would
propose to Western powers sanction measures, such as denial of
visas, against some Serb officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
