<HEADLINE> Central American Summit Set For Managua on Sept. 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Presidents from Costa Rica,
Nicaragua, El Salvador, Honduras and Guatemala will meet on
September 2 in Managua, said Costa Rican Foreign Minister Fernando
Naranjo today.
</P>
<P>
They will review the ongoing integration-process reform
outlined at the last Summit in Panama.
</P>
<P>
The Panama Summit has initiated the dialogue with the
assistance of the Inter-American Development Bank and the Economic
Commission for Latin America. The discussions will focus on the
reduction and reform of the Central American integration
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Several such organizations, created 30 years ago, are currently
obsolete, while others can be merged, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from Central American countries gathered last
week in Managua to review the documents to be submitted in the
upcoming summit, said Naranjo.
</P>
<P>
"We are supervising the results of the accords issued in
Panama," he said. This is "the most important task" for the
foreign ministries of the region, he added. 
