<HEADLINE> Trade Between Mexico, Costa Rica Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica's Foreign Trade
Minister Jose Manuel Salazar today commended the growing trade
between his country and Mexico since the signing of a bilateral
free trade agreement in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica's exports to Mexico rose from 15 million
U.S. dollars in 1995 to 51 million dollars in 1996, and are
expected to reach 64 million dollars in 1997 and 80 million
dollars in 1998, Salazar said.
</P>
<P>
The free trade agreement was sharply criticized by various
sectors in the two countries in 1994 when the accord was signed
during the economic crisis in Mexico and Costa Rica. But Salazar
rejected the criticism, saying that the agreement was good for
Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica's exports to Mexico have been up since 1996. The
figure dropped from 23 million dollars to 15 million dollars in
1994-95.
</P>
<P>
The minister said 10 percent of 400 million dollars of direct
foreign investment in Costa Rica came from Mexico last year. But
before the accord, no such Mexican investments had occurred in
Costa Rica, Salazar added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
