<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves 542 Million Dollar Credit for Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today approved a one-year standby credit of 542 million
U.S. dollars for Ukraine to support its economic program.
</P>
<P>
Some 49 million dollars of the fund will be made available
immediately.
</P>
<P>
The fund will back a 1997/98 program to reduce inflation and
increase international reserves of the Ukraine and lay the basis
for the country's economic recovery and growth through structural
reforms.
</P>
<P>
The program aims to cut inflation from 40 percent in 1996 to 12
percent in 1998 and raise the country's gross international
reserves from the equivalent of 5.2 weeks of imports in 1996 to
7.4 weeks of imports in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The program also foresees a cut in the consolidated budget
deficit to below 4.6 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) in
1997 and 4.5 percent of GDP in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine joined the IMF in September 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
