<HEADLINE> Li Peng's Singapore Visit Deepens Bilateral Ties-Lee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng's
visit to Singapore will deepen the Singapore-China relations and
further bilateral cooperation, Singapore Deputy Prime Minister Lee
Hsien Loong said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a welcoming meeting for Li Peng by Singapore's
business community, Lee said bilateral economic ties have steadily
improved, and trade, tourism and investment have all expanded
strongly.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade between 1992 and 1996 doubled and Singapore
companies continue to invest steadily in China, he said, adding
that Singapore investment in China has exceeded 23 billion U.S.
dollars, making it the 5th largest investor in China.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore projects in China reflect the Singapore
government's commitment to bilateral cooperation, and provide a
tangible focus for the development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that a total of 6,900 projects have been initiated
by Singapore companies in China, in diversified areas ranging from
manufacturing to the development of industrial parks, property and
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
"Singapore businessmen are keen to invest in China. They sense
the bountiful opportunities and the prospect for continued
dramatic progress," Lee said.
</P>
<P>
He stated that China is going through a period of "exciting
change." Its economic reforms have steadily opened up China's
economy to the rest of the world, he added.
</P>
<P>
The result has been rapid economic growth, a steady increase in
exports, and a dramatic improvement in the standards of living of
the people, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
"China has also become the single largest destination for
foreign investment among developing countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
"China now enjoys high growth and low inflation, a scenario
which must be envied by many economic planners," Lee said.
</P>
</TEXT>
