<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Sees Long-Term Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said
today that his country's economy will keep a sound momentum of
growth for a long time.
</P>
<P>
"Various factors show that China's economy will maintain its
sound momentum of growth," Li told Singaporean businessmen in an
address.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier is in Singapore for a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
He said "enormous changes" have taken place since China adopted
the reform and opening-up policy in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
"Economic reform and reform in other fields are developing in
depth."
</P>
<P>
A socialist market economy was gradually taking shape and an
overall pattern of opening-up had come into being. A relatively
high economic growth has been maintained and the living standards
in both urban and rural areas have been notably improved, the
premier enumerated.
</P>
<P>
China has formulated a development plan for the last five years
of this century and long-range objectives until the year 2010, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The coming 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of
China will make significant arrangements for China's reform,
opening-up, modernization drive and in particular, ways to develop
the socialist market economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It will inevitably have a major and profound impact on China's
future development.
</P>
<P>
"We have recovered smoothly from the period of grief after the
passing of Deng Xiaoping. China enjoys political stability,
economic development and ethnic unity and the Chinese people are
living and working in peace and contentment.
</P>
<P>
"Under the collective central leadership with President Jiang
Zemin at the core, the Chinese people are marching with full
confidence toward the goal of modernization along the road of
building socialism with Chinese characteristics initiated by Deng
Xiaoping," Li said.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that Hong Kong will enjoy long-term
prosperity and stability following its return to China.
</P>
<P>
"The entire Chinese people, including compatriots in Hong Kong,
and the international community have full confidence about its
long-term prosperity and stability," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the smooth return of Hong Kong to the motherland, the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) government has
been operating smoothly and the Basic Law of the HKSAR has been
effectively implemented, the premier said.
</P>
<P>
Despite a rosy future for China's economy, the premier also
pointed out that there are still difficulties.
</P>
<P>
"China has made remarkable achievements in economic
development. However, viewed as a whole, its development is uneven
and its per capita income is still pretty low. There still exist
quite a few problems and difficulties on our way ahead," Li said.
</P>
<P>
"It will take up several more decades of hard work to realize
modernization and reach the development level of moderately
developed countries," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
