<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Urges Closer Economic Ties with ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng today
called for enhanced cooperation with the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) countries, saying it would contribute to
growth and stability in the region as well as in the world.
</P>
<P>
"The cooperation between China and ASEAN nations should be
oriented toward the 21st century," Li told a group of Singapore
businessmen on the last day of his three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
"The cooperation... is not an expediency, it is rather a
long-term strategy," Li said. "It is conducive not only to our
respective economic development, but also to peace and stability
of the Asia-Pacific region and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
"It also serves as the foundation for political diversity in
the world," Li said.
</P>
<P>
China and ASEAN countries will both benefit from expanded
cooperation, as their economies are "highly complementary to each
other," Li said.
</P>
<P>
China needs to learn from the ASEAN countries' experience in
developing the economy, and it could also provide a huge market
for ASEAN exports, he said.
</P>
<P>
While reaffirming China's commitment to promote trade with
southeast Asian countries, Li appealed to the ASEAN governments to
create more favorable conditions for cooperation between both
sides' business communities.
</P>
<P>
"Our market will continue to be open to ASEAN countries," he
said, adding that China is also ready to invest in southeast
Asia, setting up solely Chinese-funded or joint ventures there
with capital and technology.
</P>
<P>
The premier urged the two sides to open up "flexible and
multi-formed" channels and exploit new areas of cooperation,
including infrastructure, technological transfer, poverty
alleviation and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand, Vietnam, Laos and Myanmar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
