<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parish Retires from NBA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Robert Parish, the all time
games leader, announced his retirement on Monday on the cable
television network ESPN after his record 21 seasons in NBA.
</P>
<P>
After capturing a fourth NBA championship with the Chicago
Bulls last season, the former Boston Celtics pilot set a record of
the most NBA games played -- 1,611 games.
</P>
<P>
Parish, 43, playing 14 seasons for the Celtics, has led the
Celtics to NBA titles in 1981, 1984 and 1986 with teammate Larry
Bird and Kevin McHale. All three were among the 50 Greatest
Players selected last year.
</P>
<P>
The 2.13-meter center, known as "the Chief", averaged 14.5
points and 9.1 rebounds per game. He is the 13th on the all-time
scoring list with 23,334 points, while his 14,715 rebounds and
2,361 blocks is sixth all time. The durable center's 10,117
defensive boards are an NBA record.
</P>
<P>
Parish played for the Golden State Warriors and Charlotte
Hornets before joining the Bulls last year. Wearing the uniform
with the household number 00, the nine-time All-Star shot 53.7
percent from the field and 72.1 percent from the line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
