<HEADLINE> Thailand, Mauritius to Enhance Commercial Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Mauritius have
promised to double bilateral trade to 50 million U.S. dollars by
the year 2000, according to Thai Foreign Minister Prachuab
Chaiyasarn.
</P>
<P>
Plans for closer commercial ties were discussed during a
five-day visit to Mauritius by Prachuab, which concluded on
Sunday, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Thailand and Mauritius would sign an agreement in Bangkok on
October 1, when Mauritius Finance Minister Vasant Kumar Nunwaree
visits to Thailand, Prachuab told the local press.
</P>
<P>
Other possible links included joint ventures in Tuna fisheries
by using cold storage facilities in Mauritius, and its free port
as a gateway to other African markets, Prachuab said.
</P>
<P>
Mauritius would support Thailand's effort to become a member of
the Indian Ocean Rim Association for Regional Cooperation and, in
return, Thailand would back Mauritius' bid for observer status in
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), Prachuab said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
