<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Confidence Rising In Hong Kong And Inland Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Consumer confidence in Hong
Kong and inland areas has gone up recently, according to a survey
by Visa International.
</P>
<P>
It shows an overall consumer confidence index for Hong Kong of
60.5 points on a 100-point scale, up from 59.1 points at the end
of last year. Confidence in the Hong Kong economy as a whole
soared to 77 points from 66.7 points at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The overall consumer confidence index for China's inland areas,
which was first included in these surveys last December, jumped to
74 points from 67 points.
</P>
<P>
The survey indicates that consumers in Guangzhou, the capital
of Guangdong province, a showcase of market economy reforms in
China, are more confident than those in Beijing and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
In general, Chinese consumers are optimistic about the standard
of living, overall economic performance, and their regular
earnings.
</P>
<P>
Visa International began the survey of consumer confidence in
the Asia-Pacific region in 1993 on a six-month basis based on five
indicators: job opportunities, the overall economic situation,
regular earnings, stock market performance, and standard of
living. 
</P>
</TEXT>
