<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's State-Owned Enterprises Getting Rid Of Unfit Managers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 26 (Xinhua) -- North China's Shanxi Province
has removed 179 general managers of local state-owned enterprises
who were considered unqualified, and has gotten younger, more
competent candidates to take their place.
</P>
<P>
The unqualified people were lowered in grade or dismissed
because of incompetence as part of a recent provincial government
campaign to look into the quality of enterprise leaders.
</P>
<P>
Local governments studied the record of nearly 18,961 managers
of 4,040 state-owned enterprises, or 73 percent of the province's
total, and promoted 2,057 people as new general managers.
</P>
<P>
Younger people who passed the requisite examinations were
chosen in their place.
</P>
<P>
Local officials say that the move is meant to revitalize the
local economy. The incompetence of many state-owned enterprise
managers has long been considered a major cause of the poor
performance of the sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
