<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Support For Education In Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 26 (Xinhua) -- A World-Bank and
Chinese-government funded project will begin this year to help
southwestern parts of China improve basic education facilities in
poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
The World bank has long aided poor parts of China in education
and this is the second project since 1982 in southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Projects have been completed in Guizhou, Hunan, Shanxi, Hubei,
Yunnan and Shaanxi provinces. In 20 Yunnan counties that have
benefited from World Bank assistance, nearly 97 percent of the
school age children are in school.
</P>
<P>
The bank will provide 90 million US dollars worth of
low-interest loans to China this time, and the Chinese government
is expected to provide the same amount of supporting funds.
</P>
<P>
The project will help train more teachers, build more schools
and purchase more books and teaching equipment.
</P>
<P>
China says it will spread nine-year compulsory education
nationwide by the end of this century. According to the State
Commission of Education, China has received a total of 330 million
dollars of loans from World Bank to fund such projects.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has also established a special
department in charge of World Bank loans and supporting funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
