<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China City Uses More Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Wuzhou, in southwest China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, has led the region in recent
years in the use of overseas investment which hit over 1.7 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The No.2 Xijiang Bridge, which is being constructed at an
estimated cost of 1.3 billion yuan, represents the city's first
endeavor to use overseas capital to build projects of the kind.
</P>
<P>
When completed, an 8.6-km road to the east of the bridge will
improve traffic conditions between Guangxi and Guangdong. The road
will be completed at a cost of 39 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The New World Development Co. Ltd. from Hong Kong has invested
2.3 billion yuan to expand and upgrade a first-grade highway
linking Wuzhou and Fengkai.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong company recently invested another 90 million US
dollars to build a 100-km second-grade highway to Hezhou City.
</P>
<P>
The city's agricultural development and tourism have also
emerged as hot fields for overseas investments.
</P>
<P>
The city received 60 million US dollars in loans from Austria
to construct the Jingnan Water Conservation Project. The city's
largest-ever overseas funded project was built at a cost of 107
million US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0289 </DOCNO>
