<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Takes First Diving Gold at Universiade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MESSINA, Sicily, August 25 (Xinhua) -- China took the first gold
medal of the Universiade diving tournament as Lu Haisong scored 275.16
points in the final here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Lu, a student from Nanjing Physical Culture and Sports Education
Institute, beat her compatriot Chen Lixia to the second place.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Lu, whose best result was merely a sixth place
finishing at the national champions cup, ranked only fourth after
afternoon's semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
In the five-dive final, Lu collected 62.40 point from her second
dive of forward one and a half samersaults at pike position, the
highest score of the competitions.
</P>
<P>
With a low total degree of difficulty compared with Chen and two
American divers Jennifer Lingamfelter and Michelle Rojohn, Lu executed
all her five dives successfully and got 58.32, 51.06, 52.56 and 50.82
points in a row to secure the first place.
</P>
<P>
Chen Lixia, who led the six divers into the final, managed to take
the silver medal despite of catching a cold in the morning.
</P>
<P>
Chen got only 49.92 points from her second dive and that proved
fatal to her. Yet her 266.85 total is still 1.05 points more than
Rojohn who finished third.
</P>
<P>
Jin Haiquan, coach of the Chinese diving team, was quite satisfied
with the results:"Our divers did quite good today. It was a long and
tiring day for them as they competed from 8 in the morning till 9 at
night."
</P>
<P>
"The American divers are quite strong and they also put up a good
performance in the final." Jin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
