<HEADLINE> U.S. Welcomes U.N. Probe into Hutu Massacres in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- the United States on Monday
welcomed a U.N. team to investigate alleged massacres of Rwandan
refugees by soldiers loyal to Congoless President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Upon the arrival of the U.N. investigative team in Kinshasa,
State Department spokesman James Rubin said the United States
wants "to have a thorough and impartial investigation to get to
the bottom of the very serious charges of massacres and atrocities
that have been made."
</P>
<P>
"The Congolese authorities have repeatedly pledged their full
cooperation with this team, and the United States has made it clear
that we expect them to keep their word," Rubin said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
According to Rubin the team's investigation will take several
months and should be completed by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Most of the slain refugees were Rwandan Hutus who had fled
into eastern Zaire in 1994 when Rwandan Tutsis took over power
in the central country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
