<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: CFC Alternatives Cause Liver Damage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The first cases of liver
disease caused by two industrial refrigerants, alternative to
chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs), had been confirmed, according to the
latest edition of The Lancet magazine.
</P>
<P>
The magazine reported that nine workers became ill after
accidental exposure to HCFC-123 and HCFC-124. HCFCs were known as
halogenated hydrochlorofluorocarbons.
</P>
<P>
CFCs, which seriously damage the ozone layer and make our
planet warmer, were banned in use in 1990 by an international
treaty in order to save the ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
The workers, employed in an unidentified Belgian smelting
facility where they drove an overhead gantry, worked in a gantry
cabin connected to the same air-conditioning system.
</P>
<P>
Some plastic piping had perforated, allowing HCFCs to leak into
the cabin.
</P>
<P>
The Lancet reported that one of the workers in the cabin became
ill with symptoms of acute hepatitis, followed soon after by
another gantry driver.
</P>
<P>
Then researchers found specific protein in liver cells taken
from the workers that are associated with HCFC toxicity.
</P>
<P>
The results of this study show that repeated exposure of human
beings to HCFCs 123 and 124 can result in serious liver injury in
high proportion of the exposed population, the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
It urged the industries to take very strict measures of
containment to prevent accidental exposure of the refrigerants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970826.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Faces Cuts Because of Financial Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Carol Bellamy, the
executive director of the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF)
said today the organization was cutting its staff by about seven
percent because of financial problems.
</P>
<P>
"The abolition of around 950 posts is offset by the creation of
500 new posts in the 1998-99 biennium, resulting in a net
reduction of about 450 posts or approximately seven percent of
staff worldwide," said Bellamy.
</P>
<P>
But she promised to try to find new jobs for those whose jobs
are abolished.
</P>
<P>
She cited two main reasons for the job cuts: a decline in funds
available for development assistance and the strengthening of the
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF employs about 6,050 staff worldwide, including 570 at
U.N. headquarters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
